let class_6_history = [

    { title: "Chapter 1 Prehistoric period ",content:`<input id="chapter" placeholder="Chapter" value="Chapter 1">
    <input class="subtitle" placeholder="Chapter Name" value="Prehistoric period">
    <div class="editor" contenteditable="true">
        <div><br></div><div>Pre Notes<ol><li>Palaeolithic &gt; Mesolithic &gt;Neolithic&gt; Copper age &gt; Iron age</li><li>Stone age upto decline of indus civilisation</li><li>Prehistoric period before development&nbsp; Script, no written records</li><li>Human evolve in africa and later migrated to other parts</li><li><b><i>Homo Erectus </i></b>: Earliest human ancestor</li></ol><div><br></div></div><div><br></div><div><div>General features of&nbsp;Palaeolithic-old stone BC 10,000<ol><li><b><i>Nomads</i></b>, use of&nbsp;<b><i>Fire</i></b>,stones,&nbsp;hunting</li><li>simple rock of quartzite used&nbsp;</li><li><b>Pimpet cave Painting in MP</b>, woman tied her child to her waist,&nbsp;</li><li>Old Stone Ages tools found at</li><ol><li>MP- Soan river, Pimet caves, bhimbetka caves</li><li>Rajasthan - luni valley</li><li>Karnataka - Pagalkhat</li><li>AP - Kurnool caves</li><li>TN - Kanchi, vellore</li><li>Soan valley, potwar plateau, pakistan</li><li>Siwalik hills</li><li>Adamgarh hill in narmada valley</li><li>Attirampakkam near chennai</li></ol><li><b>Kolidhiwa</b>, Belan Valley<ol><li>presence of all three stages</li></ol></li></ol></div><ol></ol><div><br></div><div><span style="font-size: 16.8px; -webkit-text-fill-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"><b>LOWER PALEOLITHIC</b></span></div><div><ol><li><b>Homo Erectus</b>&nbsp;ancestors of homo sapiens&nbsp;</li><li>homo erectus language not complex, may had express sounds or few words</li><li>first site discovered by <b>Robert 1863</b>, pallavaram near chennai</li><li><b>Primitive tools</b>, hand axes, cleavers used for hunting</li><li>Acheulian tools, polyhedrons, spheroids, hand axes</li><li>Lived in <b><i>open and caves</i></b></li><li>Rock shelter evidence:&nbsp;<b><i>Bhimbetka</i></b>&nbsp;in mp</li><li><b>Hominin,&nbsp;</b>immediate ancestor of homo sapiens<ol style="font-style: italic;"><li><i>in india only found at Hathnora near hoshangabad in MP</i></li><li><i>Cranium name: <b>Narmada Hum</b></i></li></ol></li><li>In <b><i>Narmada Valley</i></b><ol><li>fossils of Elephas Namadicus</li><li>Stegodon ganesa, elephant</li><li>Bos namadicus, wild cattle</li><li>Equus Namadicus, great horse</li><li>Teeth of Equus, evidence of water buffalo</li><li>Equus refers to genus of horses, asses, zebras</li></ol></li><li><i>Acheulian and Sohanian&nbsp;<b>Hand Axes Tools</b>, Two cultures<ol><li>Acheulian</li><ol><li>use of hand axes and cleavers</li></ol><li>Sohan industry</li><ol><li>used only chopper and chopping tools</li><li>name form Sohan river of pakistan</li></ol></ol></i></li></ol></div><div><span style="font-size: 16.8px;"><b>MIDDLE PALAEOLITHIC OR MESOLITHIC</b></span></div><div><ol><li>Time around 40,000 BC in india</li><li>Species lived: <b>Homo Erectus</b></li><li>no Hominin, fossils found</li><li>Middle palaeolithic first found&nbsp;<b>HD Sankalia</b>, pravara River, Nevasa</li><li><b><i>Flake tools</i></b>&nbsp;popular in this period, scrappers, <b><i>points and borers</i></b></li><li>found in narmada, godavari, krishna, yamuna and other river valleys</li><li>People lived in open air, caves, rock shelters</li><li>but smaller tools, use of chert, jasper, quartz as raw material</li><li>a transitional phase between palaeolithic to neolithic</li><li>Emergence of&nbsp;<b>Microlithics, Small tools</b></li><li>use of bow and arrow, settlements emerged</li><li><b><i>Hunting</i></b>, <b><i>Gathering </i></b>food fishing main</li><li>people <b><i>Highly Mobile</i></b>, made temporary huts</li><li>circular huts in rock paintings</li><li>paintings of bhimbetka shows men and women goes to hunting together</li><li><b><i>Bhimbetka Caves</i></b><ol><li>paintings of animal, men and women</li><li>no snake painting</li></ol></li><li><b style="font-style: italic;">No Pottery, No Agriculture </b>evidences, but during the transitional phase from Meso to Neo agriculture starts&nbsp;</li><li>Burial of humans,&nbsp;&nbsp;<b><i>Mahadaha, UP </i></b>a man and a woman were buried together</li><li>Buried bones show evidence of Dry Deciduous Forest</li><li>Sites</li><ol><li><b>Bagor</b>, Rajasthan, largest site on river Kothari</li><li><b>Langhnaj </b>in gujarat</li><li><b>Adamgarh </b>in MP</li><li>Coastal site Teri, mumbai</li></ol></ol></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><span style="font-size: 16.8px; -webkit-text-fill-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"><b>NEOLITHIC NEW STONE AGE BC 6000 to 4000</b></span></div><div><span style="-webkit-text-fill-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"><b><i><br></i></b></span></div><div><ol><li><b><i>Domestication and Agriculture</i></b></li><li>First tamed animal:&nbsp;<b><i>Dog</i></b>, goats and cows: milk</li><li>Surplus food production, <b>S<i>elf sufficient village</i></b>s</li><li><b><i>Polished</i></b>&nbsp;Axes for hunting</li><li>now instead of living in jungle, they built mud houses</li><li>people became Semi-Nomadic</li><li>first use of&nbsp;<b><i>Pottery</i>&nbsp;</b>used for cooking, people started eating cooked food, caused dental problems</li><li>evidence of&nbsp;<b><i>drilling human tooth in Mehrgarh</i></b></li><li>practice of burying dead with animal in large urns as coffins</li><li>Terracotta figurines, use of sea shell, limestone, turquoise, lapis, lazuli, sandstone</li><li>Neolithic preceded Indus civilisation</li><li>Sharp tools,&nbsp;<b>Microliths</b></li><li>bone tools and faunal remains in kurnool AP</li><li>Baghor I and Baghor III of&nbsp;<b>Son Valley MP</b></li><li>Microliths and Hominin, in Sri Lanka</li><li><b><i>Ostrich Egg Shell</i></b>&nbsp;in AP, patne MP</li><li>Evidences also from paintings, Bhimbetka Cave, MP</li><li>Sites</li><ol><li><b>Mehrgarh</b>, Balochistan<ol><li>earliest neolithic site, aka Breadbasket of Balochistan</li><li>knowledge of herbs</li><li>people ate cooked food, caused&nbsp;<b><i>dental&nbsp;&nbsp;</i></b>problems</li><li>evidence of drilling tooth</li><li>terracotta figurines, glazed faience beads</li></ol></li><li><b><b>Burzahom,&nbsp;</b>Kashmir</b></li><ol><li>contemporary to Harappan site</li><li>evidence of megalithic, lived in pit houses in order to escape weather</li><li>domestication of sheep, goat</li><li>burial of wild dog and antler horn</li></ol><li><b>Koldihwa&nbsp;</b>Belan Valley<ol><li>presence of neolithic, Chalcolithic, Iron age</li><li>northern Vindhyas, middle part of Narmada Valley</li></ol></li><li>Neolithic site of ganga valley</li><ol><li><b>Lehuradeva, UP,&nbsp;</b>early rice cultivation</li><li><b>Chopani, UP</b></li><li>chirand, senuwar, Mahagara</li><li>in this region rice, pea, green gram, mustard</li></ol><li>Neolithic site in Eastern India</li><ol><li>mainly in bihar and WB</li><li>Birbhanpur, WB</li><li>Chirand, Bihar</li><li>founded shouldered axes</li><li>Veerapuram in Andhra Pradesh and Paiyampalli&nbsp;in Tamil Nadu</li></ol><li>South India</li><ol><li>mainly AP, Karnataka, TN</li><li>Ramapuram, Veerapuram AP</li><li><b>Paiyampalli&nbsp;</b>Tamil Nadu</li><li>sites near granite hills with water sources</li></ol><li>North East<ol><li>appeared very late</li><li>Daojali, Hading, Sarutaru in Assam region</li><li>Evidence of shifting cultivation</li><li>wooden memorials for dead</li></ol></li><li>Belan valley UP</li><li>Brahmagiri, Hallur</li><li>Kodekal in Karnataka</li><li>Utnur in AP</li></ol></ol></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><span style="font-size: 16.8px; -webkit-text-fill-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"><b>CHALCOLITHIC COPPER STONE  BC 3000-1500</b></span></div><div><ol><li>use of&nbsp;<b><i>Copper</i></b>, and further small tools</li><li>smelting metal ore and crafting metal artifacts</li><li>domestication of cows, sheep, goats, pigs</li><li><b>No Horses</b> were not found and <b><i>Bull as symbol</i></b></li><li>they ate <b>Beef</b></li><li>crops: wheat and rice</li><li>started eating cooked food</li><li>as agriculture increased, practice of Slash and Burn increased</li><li>evidence of <b><i>black and red pottery</i></b></li><li><b><i>No burnt brick</i></b>&nbsp;evidence, use of burnt brick in Indus valley, lived in thatched houses made of mud bricks</li><li>no written evidence found of this period</li><li>evidence of Infant mortality rates high, burial of large number of children in western Maharashtra</li></ol></div><div>Chalcolithic vs Harappan<ol><li>rural ----urban</li><li>copper----bronze</li><li>lived near hilly land or rivers---- urbanisation</li></ol></div><div><br></div><div><span style="-webkit-text-fill-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"><b><br></b></span></div><div><span style="-webkit-text-fill-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"><b><br></b></span></div><div><span style="font-size: 16.8px; -webkit-text-fill-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"><b>IRON AGE BC  1500-600&nbsp;ARYANS</b></span></div><div><ol><li>tools made up of iron</li><li><b style="font-style: italic;">rig veda time, aryans&nbsp;</b></li><li>age megalithic burials, large stones</li><li>black and red pottery, iron artifacts</li><li>Sites</li><ol><li><b>Hallur</b> and <b>Maski</b> Karnataka</li><li>Karnataka <b>Nagarjunakonda</b> AP</li><li>Adichanallur TN</li><li>Chirand</li><li>Daojali Hading</li><li>Mahagarha, MP</li><li>Paiyampalli</li></ol></ol></div><div>Some Alloys<ol><li>iron+chromium=stainless steel</li><li>iron+magnesium=steel</li><li>copper+lead=bronze</li><li>copper+zinc=brass</li></ol><div><br></div><div><br></div></div><div><div><span style="font-size: 16.8px;">Sites</span></div><div><span style="font-size: 16.8px;">I. Tamil Nadu-&nbsp;</span>&nbsp;Attirampakkam</div><div>2.Andhra&nbsp;Pradesh- Kurnool&nbsp;</div><div>3. Madhya Pradesh- Pimpet Cave&nbsp;<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span></div><div>4. Karnataka-Pagal Khat</div></div><div><br></div><div>Map 1</div><div><img src="images/historical%20sites.JPG"></div><div><br></div><div>Map 2</div><div><img src="images/neolithic%20sites.JPG"></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div></div>
    </div>`}




    ,{ title: "Chapter 2 Indus Valley Civilization Copper Age ",content:`<input id="chapter" placeholder="Chapter" value="Chapter 2">
    <input class="subtitle" placeholder="Chapter Name" value="Indus Valley Civilization Copper Age">
    <div class="editor" contenteditable="true">
        <div><br></div><div><br></div><div>First metal used : <b>Copper</b>&nbsp;&gt; stone age(Chalcolithic) Copper Age</div><div><b>Copper Age: Indus Valley Civilization, Harappa</b></div><div><br></div><div><b>Harappa</b><ol><li>Intro</li><ol><li>1921: Harappa: Daya Ram Sahni</li><li>dated: 2300 to 1750 BC approximate</li><li>civilisation appeared in north western part of india and pakistan</li><li>Neolithic site: Mehrgarh(pre harappa)</li><li>first encounter: 1856 while railway lines on bank of river Ravi, well burnt bricks and ruins, much of the structure was destroyed and bricks were used</li><li><b>Cunningham</b> first ASI, visited place in 1853</li><li>Observation: No uniformity in cultures, at different places in india, cultures were developing at different rate, cultural mosaic during time of Harappa</li></ol><li>Area<ol><li>west: <b>Sutkagendor</b> Pakistan</li><li>north: <b>Shortughai</b> Afghanistan</li><li>east: <b>Alamgirpur</b>, UP</li><li>south: <b>Daimabad</b>, Maharashtra</li><li>Core areas: pakistan, gujarat, rajasthan, haryana, sindh</li><li>Indus region <b>mehrgarh</b> early agriculture and domestication</li></ol></li><li>4 Stages of Harappa<ol><li>pre harappan<ol><li>Eastern balochistan</li><li><b>mehrgarh</b>: balochistan shows pre harappan, nomadic life</li></ol></li><li>early harappan<ol><li><b>gradual growth of towns</b> in indus valley, rural to urban life</li><li>koti diji sindh&nbsp;</li></ol></li><li>mature harappan<ol><li><b>elaborate town planning</b></li><li>kalibangan&nbsp;</li></ol></li><li>late harappan<ol><li><b>decline of Harappa</b></li><li>lothal, trade between Harappan and mesopotamian</li></ol></li></ol></li><li><b>Town planning</b></li><ol><li>Major Cities and Towns<ol><li>Harappa punjab, pak</li><li>Mohenjo Daro, pak</li><li>Dholavira, lothal, Surkotada, gujarat,</li><li>kalibangan, rajasthan,</li><li>Banawali and&nbsp; Rakhigarhi, haryana</li></ol></li><li>grid system, streets and lanes at right angle</li><li>Citadel , a high place in Mohenjodaro</li><li>Lower town, may be for common people</li><li>North: narrow, elevated, East: broad and lowered</li><li><b>multi storied</b> houses with flat roofs</li><li><b>no windows</b>&nbsp;on ground floor, <b>dustbins<i> </i></b>outside of houses</li><li>large scale use of burnt bricks and absent of stone buildings</li><li>houses had <b style="font-style: italic;">well and bathroom&nbsp;</b></li><li>Well drainage system</li><li><b>Drainage</b> system, great bath, public hall, street lights</li><li><b>Manholes</b> at regular interval</li></ol><li><b>Economic Life</b></li><ol><li><b>barter</b> system</li><li>agriculture, artisans, traders, weavers, potters, blacksmiths</li><li>progress in agriculture, industry, crafts, trade</li><li>wheat barley, sesame, mustard, cotton, <b>double cropping</b> system</li><li>animals goats, sheep, buffalo domestication</li><li><b>use of horse not identified, only at Surkotada, Guj</b></li><li>buffalo, cattles called <b><i>Zebu</i></b>, gharial</li><li>metal craft, bronze and copper</li><li>gold and silver&nbsp;&nbsp;ivory, precious stones ornaments,&nbsp;</li><li>red and black pottery</li><li>foreign trade with mesopotamia, afghanistan</li><li><b>cotton</b> and woolen dresses, dhoti shawl dresses</li><li>tools made up of copper and bronze</li><li>blades mad of Rohri Chert, a fine grained sedimentary</li></ol><li><b>Trade</b></li><ol><li>trade and exchange activities with mesopotamian</li><li>seals found in sumerian sites, oman, bahrani, iraq, iran</li><li><b>Cuneiform</b>(early writing system) inscription mention trade between Harappan and mesopotamian</li><li>mention of Meluhha in above, refers to Indus region</li></ol><li><b>Weights</b><ol><li>Ratio of weight is double: 1,2,4,8,16,32</li><li>use of <b>binary<i> </i></b>system</li></ol></li><li><b>Handicrafts</b></li><ol><li>seal markers, doll makers</li><li>terracotta figures of dolls</li><li><b>dancing girl</b> figure of Mohenjodaro made up of bronze</li><li>statue of <b>man with beard</b> made of limestones,&nbsp;Mohenjo-daro</li><li>use of copper, bronze, gold silver, weights out of stone</li><li>motifs with geometrical patterns</li><li>hundreds of rectangular seals</li><li>with pictures bull, cart, dove, boats</li><li>beads/artifacts of harappa found at mesopotamian sites</li><li>pottery, motifs with fish scale design, intersecting patterns</li><li><b>Rohri chert</b> : a fine grained sedimentary rock, was found in the region of Rohri in Pakistan.for making stone blades and tools.</li></ol><li><b>Script</b></li><ol><li>pictorial writings 400 to 600 signs</li><li>right to left</li><li><b>Boustrophedon </b>method<b>:</b> writing in reverse direction in alternative lines</li><li>yet to be deciphered</li></ol><li><b>Religion</b></li><ol><li>pashupati the lord shiva sitting in yogic posture with 3 faces 2 horns</li><li>surrounded by 4 animals: <b>elephant, tiger, rhino,buffalo</b></li><li>mother goddess, lingam, trident, <b>pipal tree<i> </i></b>worship</li><li>belief in ghosts and evil forces</li><li><b>burial</b> of dead along with urns, food, Ornaments</li><li>complete or post-cremation burial</li><li>use <b>coffins</b> at <b>lothal</b>, pot burials</li><li>no evidence of Sati</li></ol><li><b>decline</b><ol><li>fire, civil war no clear view&nbsp;</li><li>natural calamities</li><li>invasion of aryans,&nbsp; destroyed their town</li><li>heap of bones found in Mohenjo Daro shows invasion of foreigners</li></ol></li></ol><div><br></div><div><b>Sites</b></div><div><ol><li>Intro:</li><ol><li>Mohenjodaro(mound of dead): Larkana District of Sindh pakistan</li><li>Chanhudaro, Kot Diji: Sindh, pakistan</li><li>Rupar punjab</li><li>Kalibangan: Rajasthan</li><li>Lothal, Surkotada, Dholavira: Gujarat</li><li>Banawali Haryana</li></ol><li><b>Mohenjo Daro,&nbsp;</b><b>Great Bath, Granary&nbsp;</b></li><ol><li>1922, by&nbsp;R. D. Banerji</li><li>a.k.a Mound of Deads</li><li>Area: Sindh Province, pakistan</li><li>Near Indus River</li><li><b>public bathing place&nbsp;</b><ol><li>size: 39x23x8, flights of steps, North and South</li><li>side rooms for changing</li><li>evidence of stairs, courtyard</li><li>built of burnt bricks and sealed with a lining of <b>bitumen</b> to prevent leak</li></ol></li><li>Two distinct areas &gt; citadel and lower town</li><li>with great bath,&nbsp;<b>large granary or warehouse<i>&nbsp;</i></b>150 x 50 feet at Mohenjodaro</li><li>famous <b>dancing girl</b></li><li>figure of <b>pashupati</b></li><li><b>Priest king</b> image with beard</li></ol><li><b>Kalibangan Rajasthan</b></li><ol><li>by Luigi Pio Tessitori and later A Ghosh</li><li>Findings<ol><li>Ploughed fields</li><li>Black bangles</li><li>Fire altars</li><li>Charging bull</li><li>Bones of camels</li></ol></li><li>Circular and rectangular burials</li><li><b>no drainage system found</b>, bricks use were earthen one not baked</li></ol><li><b>Dholavira Gujarat</b></li><ol><li>1990 by RS Bisht</li><li>large reservoirs, elaborate drainage system</li><li>found 3 citadels, signboard with indus script</li></ol><li><b>Lothal</b></li><ol><li>city divided into <b>6 sections</b>, each section built on wide platform</li><li>artificial <b>dockyard</b>, found near Sabarmati river</li><li><b>trade</b> with mesopotamia, found iranian seals</li><li>raised <b>warehouse</b> at height of 3.5 meters, anti flood design</li><li><b>bead making factory</b>, button seal</li><li>earliest <b>rice </b>cultivation</li><li><b>pot furnace</b> found</li><li>sanitary and drainage system</li></ol><li><b>Sutkagendor Afghanistan</b></li><ol><li>on bank of dasht river near iran border</li><li>coastal town, western border of Civilisation</li></ol><li><b>Kot Diji</b></li><ol><li>pre harappan site, in sindh</li><li>found statue of bull and mother goddess</li></ol><li><b>Ropar</b> Punjab</li><ol><li>excavated by YD sharma</li></ol><li><b>Chanhudaro</b></li><ol><li>in sindh, no fortified citadel found</li><li>industrial town, factories of figurines, seals, toys</li><li>bead making factory</li></ol><li><b>Banawali</b></li><ol><li>hisar, haryana, high quality barley&nbsp;</li></ol><li><b>Mitathal</b> Haryana</li><ol><li>found cartewheels</li></ol><li><b>Alamgirpur</b></li><ol><li>meerut, UP, eastern boundary of Civilization</li><li>copper tools, fossils, bones</li></ol><li><b>Surkotada Gujarat</b></li><ol><li><b>remains of horse</b></li></ol><li><b>Rakhigarhi</b> Haryana<ol><li><b>terracotta&nbsp;wheels</b>, toys, figurines, pottery. Large site, partially excavated</li></ol></li><li>Bhagatrav Gujarat</li><li><b>Amri Sindh</b></li><ol><li><span>Remains of rhinoceros</span></li></ol></ol><div>Northern Most: Manda Jammu</div></div><div>Southern Most: Malwa, Gujarat</div><div>Easternmost: Alamgirpur, UP</div><div>WesternMost: Sutkagendor Gujarat</div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><b>Extra Notes</b><ol><li><span>Archaeological Survey of India 1861 by&nbsp;Cunningham&nbsp;</span></li><li><span>Mehrgarh&nbsp;– the Precursor to Indus Civilisation</span></li><li><span>Mehrgarh&nbsp;is a Neolithic site.&nbsp;</span></li><li><span>It is located near the Bolan Basin of Balochistan in Pakistan. It is one of the earliest sites known.&nbsp;</span></li><li><span>It shows evidence of farming and herding done by man in very early times</span></li></ol><div><br></div><div><img src="images/sites%20of%20indus%20valley.JPG"></div><div><br></div><div><br></div></div><div><img src="images/indus%20valley%20north%20west.JPG"></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div></div><div><br></div>
    </div>`}


,{ title: "Chapter 3 Vedic Period ",content:`<input id="chapter" placeholder="Chapter" value="Chapter 3">
    <input class="subtitle" placeholder="Chapter Name" value="Vedic Period">
    <div class="editor" contenteditable="true">
        <div><br></div><div><span style="-webkit-text-fill-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"><b><i>Order of Periods</i></b></span><ol></ol></div><div><ol><li>Paleolithic(lower,middle,upper) Period</li><li>Mesolithic</li><li>Neolithic</li><li>Copper Age, Indus, Harappan</li><ol><li>Ochre colored pottery ware found</li><li>jars, storage, bowls, basins</li></ol><li>Iron Age, Aryans, Transition into Vedic Period</li><li>Rise of 16 Mahajanapadas</li></ol></div><div><b><i>Few Notes:</i></b></div><div><ol><li>Conventional view of timeline of history would simply shift theme from indus through vedic to age of Mahajanapadas</li><li>vedic age no written material, transmitted orally</li><li>chalcolithic overlap with early vedic period</li><li>later vedic with painted grey ware culture(potter black red) of Iron age</li><li>Samhita earliest text of rig veda</li></ol></div><div><br></div><div>Aryans: Rig Veda or Iron Age<ol><li><div>Harappan decline by 1500 BC</div><ol></ol></li><li><div>Aryans came in north west and punjab region</div></li><li>migrated to india through Khyber&nbsp; and bolan passes</li><li>shepherds from central asia about 4000 years ago</li><li>place of settlement : Arya Vardham</li><li>livelihood: Cattle herding</li><li>language: indo-aryan, sanskrit</li></ol><div><br></div><div><b>Origin of Aryas</b><ol><li>arctic region, germany</li><li>tilak proposed they were from arctic region</li><li>widely accepted: theory of southern russia</li><li>Aryans, eastern european central asia north of black sea</li></ol><div><b>Literature Sources</b><ol><li>language vedic sanskrit</li><li>Rig veda oldest</li><li>Later yajur(rituals), sama(music), atharva(magic spells)</li><li><b><i>Samhitas</i></b> main collection of Vedic Hymns<ol><li>they explain ritualist texts and explain social and importance of rituals</li><li>Each Samhitas contains added Text: <b><i>Brahmanas</i></b>, commentaries on hymns</li><li>Each Brahmanas contains <b><i>Aranyaka</i></b> and an <b><i>Upanishad</i></b></li></ol></li><li>Rig veda being earliest samhita<ol><li>contains 10 books</li><li>2 to 7 early&nbsp; period</li><li>1,8,9,10 later period</li></ol></li><li>Zend Avesta: P<b>ersian/iranian book of Zoroastrian</b>, evidence of early home of aryans</li></ol><div><b><i>Pre-Aryan, Late Harappan and chalcolithic Period</i></b><ol><li>pre Harappan is chalcolithic period, before vedic age</li><li>chalcolithic copper age of indus civilization</li><li>some farming in chalcolithic period, and later extensive agriculture in Neolithic</li><li>during indus civilization shows evidence of domestication, houses of mud, farming, granary house, rice, wheat, barley, use of copper in large terms</li><li>Ochre colored Pottery Ware Culture</li><ol><li>found during chalcolithic in northern part</li><li>red slips and ochre color, black painted designs of jars, bowls</li><li>OCP sites can be termed as copper hoard culture</li><li>terracotta ornaments of toys and animals</li></ol></ol></div></div></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><b><i>Early Vedic Age or Rig Veda BC 1500-1000</i></b><ol><li>At time of compile of rig veda aryans lived in Sindhu, now in pak</li><li>Sapta Sindhu land of seven rivers<ol><li>indus, Sindhu</li><li>jhelum, Vatista</li><li>ravi, Purushni</li><li>chenab, Askini</li><li>satluj, Sutudri</li><li>beas, Vipasa</li><li>Saraswati, modern ghaggar and hakra&nbsp;</li></ol></li><li>Rig Veda</li><ol><li>consists 1028 hymns, in praise of gods</li><li>10 mandals, consists of Samhita, family books</li><li>2 to 8 family books</li><li>3 mandal, Gayatri Mantra</li><li>8 mandal, Kanva's family</li><li>9 mandal, Soma</li><li>Upveda: Ayurved</li><li>Shakala Shakha, surviving recension</li></ol><li>Sama Veda</li><ol><li>collection of verses taken from rig</li><li>1,810 melodies, Drupada Raga sung by Tansen</li><li>Upved: Gandharva Veda</li></ol><li>Yajur Veda</li><ol><li>ritual and sacrifices</li><li>two parts</li><li>Shukla or White yajur</li><li>Krishna or Black yajur</li><li>Upved: Dhanur</li></ol><li>Atharva Veda</li><ol><li>black magic</li><li>non aryan work</li><li>Upved: Shilpa</li></ol><li>Brahmanas</li><ol><li>rules for performance of sacrificial</li><li>each veda has Brahmanas attached to it</li><li>Satapatha Brahmanas, attached to Yajur Veda</li></ol><li>Aranyakas</li><ol><li>forest books, philosophical work</li></ol><li>Upanishads<ol><li>108 Upanishads</li><li>dwell on Atman and Brahman</li><li>focus on Philosophy about life, universe, <b><i>self</i></b>, sacrifice</li><li><b>Mandukyopanishad </b>contains Satyameva Jayate is largest</li><li>Chandogya Upanishad<ol><li>contains first three ashrams,&nbsp;</li><li><b><i>Brahmacharya, grihasta and vanaprastha</i></b>&nbsp;are mentioned</li><li><b><i>Sanyasa</i></b>&nbsp;developed later</li><li>two types of marriage</li><li>Anuloma: Man marry women of own or below varna&nbsp;</li><li>Pratiloma: Women marry man of lower varna</li></ol></li></ol></li><li>Vedanga<ol><li>limbs of vedas, supplementary texts</li><li><span style="font-size: 16.8px;">Shiksha<span style="white-space:pre">	</span>(Phonetics)&nbsp;</span></li><li><span style="font-size: 16.8px;">Kalpa<span style="white-space:pre">	</span>(Ritualistic<span style="white-space:pre">	</span>science)</span></li><li><span style="font-size: 16.8px;">Jyotisha<span style="white-space:pre">	</span>(Astronomy)&nbsp;</span></li><li><span style="font-size: 16.8px;">Vyakaran<span style="white-space:pre">	</span>(Grammar)&nbsp;</span></li><li><span style="font-size: 16.8px;">Nirukta<span style="white-space:pre">	</span>(Etymology)&nbsp;</span></li><li><span style="font-size: 16.8px;">Chhanda<span style="white-space:pre">	</span>(Metrics)</span></li></ol></li><li>Four Vedas: Each veda has Samhita, Brahmanas, Aryankas, Upanishads</li><li>mention of term Asva(horse) and vrishabha(bull)</li><li>hence it proves <b>no relation between Aryans and Harappan</b>, there no evidence of horse</li><li>mention of Dasas and Dasyus refers to&nbsp; non-aryans</li><li><b><i>Simyu</i></b> and <b><i>Kikata</i></b> are grouped with dasyus</li><li>Mention of Sambara defeat by Divodasa chief of Bharata Clan</li><li>Bharatas ad Tritsu ruling clans, Bharata varsha name India</li><li>Mention of Battle of Ten Kings<ol><li>on bank of River <b><i>Parushni</i></b>, aka Ravi</li><li>Sudas clans defeated Purus clan</li><li>later purus formed alliance with Bharatas, named: Kuru Clan</li></ol></li><li>people invoked support of gods in war</li></ol><div><br></div><div><b><i><br></i></b></div><div><b><i>Political Life in Rig Period</i></b><ol><li>Family(kula)&gt;Village(grama)&gt;Vis&gt;Jana&gt;Janapada(although janapada not in rig period)</li><li><b>Grama</b>: headed by <b><i>Grahmini</i></b></li><li>Villages: group of villages formed <b>Visu </b>headed by <b><i>Vishwapati</i></b></li><li><b>Jana</b>: group of villages headed by <b><i>Rajan </i></b>or King</li><li>King names as prajapati,</li><li><b>kingship was hereditary</b></li><li><b>Vrajapati</b>: officer to control territory</li><li>many chieftains formed Mahajanapadas</li><li>King assisted by </li><ol><li>Purohit: priests</li><li>Senani: Commander</li></ol><li>Assemblies</li><ol><li>Sabha: elders</li><li>Samiti: representatives of people</li><li>vidhata, assembly of tribe, military and religious functions</li><li>gana: assembly or troop</li><li>women were allowed in sabha and vidhata</li></ol><li>Rule by King, clans formed tribe or janas</li><li>but <b><i>king head limited power</i></b>, powers with Assemblies</li><li>but no mention of janapada in earlier vedic period</li><li>no tax collecting officer mention</li><li>bali as a imposed tax, some says it was voluntary</li></ol><div><br></div><div><b><i>Social Life</i></b><ol><li>Varna system, Arya Varna and Dasa Varna</li><li>warriors, priests, common people</li><li>but earlier egalitarian and later caste system</li><li>sudras came in later vedic period</li><li>Purusha Sukta</li><ol><li>brahmans: mouth</li><li>Kshatriya: arms</li><li>Vaisya: thighs</li><li>Sudras: Feet</li></ol><li>Panis means Itinerary Traders</li><li>head of family male(grihapati)- patriarchal society, women: Sapatni</li><li>women equality, attended popular ceremonies</li><li>women poets like Vishwara, apala, kosa, lopamudra&nbsp;</li><li>no caste system</li><li>monogamy and polygamy present</li><li>widow's remarriage permitted</li><li>no child marriage or sati</li><li>Agriculture<ol><li>langla and sura means plough</li><li>sita means a long narrow trench created by plough</li><li>knowledge of different seasons</li><li><b><i>barley</i></b> and <b><i>wheat</i></b> main</li></ol></li></ol><div><br></div></div></div><div><b><i>Economic Life</i></b><ol><li>Cattle rearing and agriculture<ol><li><b><i>wheat, barley, milk, curd, ghee, meat</i></b> .&nbsp;</li><li>soma and sura intoxicating drinks .</li><li>cow meat prohibited, Aghnya means not be killed</li><li>wealth in terms of cattle</li></ol></li><li><b>Gavishthi </b>means search for cows, war</li><li>donations in terms of cows, women slaves but no land donation</li><li>Rig Veda <b><i>Iron age</i></b></li><li>bringing down forests to make cultivable lands,&nbsp;</li><li>Siri means yarn, takshan means carpenters</li><li>use of copper, iron, bronze</li><li>production of cotton and woolen clothes</li><li><b>Pan </b>means<b> :Barter System exists</b></li><li>Gold coin : <b>Nishka </b>currency</li><li>Dresses</li><ol><li>men dhoti and shawl, turbans cotton and wool</li><li>women, earrings, necklace, bangles, anklets</li></ol><li><b>Religion</b></li><ol><li>worshipped natural forces Sun, Fire, Air, Sky, Trees</li><li>Usha, goddess of dawn</li><li>Aditi, Prithvi, Sinivali</li><li>no temples, no idol worship</li><li>Indira, Varna, Agni, Yaman, Varuna god of water</li><li>offering milk, ghee, grains, silk..&nbsp;</li><li>Yagas like Ashvamedha and Rajasuya</li></ol><li>bullock carts, horses and chariots used for transport</li></ol><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><b>Later Vedic Period 1000-600 BC</b><ol><li><b><i>Sama Veda: music, chantings</i></b></li><li><b><i>Atharva Veda:&nbsp; black magic, spells</i></b></li><li><b><i>Yajur period: rituals, yag</i></b></li><li>Mention of <b><i>Elephant</i></b> and <b><i>Anga and Magadha</i></b> were seen as enemies&nbsp; in Atharva veda</li><li>Aryans moved towards eastern part of country gangetic plains</li><li>Kuru Panchala region or Upper ganga valley</li><li><span style="font-size: 16.8px;"><b><i>Aitareya&nbsp;Brahmana</i></b><ol><li>South Eastern boundary into gangetic&nbsp;valley</li><li>also mention of pundras of bengal and andhras as outside of aryans identity</li><li>this shows aryanisation spread gradually form north west to south east</li></ol></span></li><li>Bali from people</li><li>Dara Shikoh,<b><i>Upanishads into Persian</i></b> in 1657</li></ol><div><br></div><div><span style="font-size: 16.8px;">Political Life</span></div><div><ol><li>Term Rashtra first appeared in this period</li><li>wars no longer for cows but for lands</li><li>no standing army</li><li>in later stages, janapadas emerged</li><li>kingdoms emerged&nbsp;</li><ol><li>kosala</li><li>videham</li><li>kuru</li><li>magadha</li><li>kasi</li><li>avanti</li><li>panchala</li></ol><li>kingship was hereditary</li><li><b>Rajasuya&nbsp;</b>and&nbsp;<b>Ashvamedha</b>&nbsp;were performed to establish his undisputed authority</li><li>power of kings increased in this period and of Assemblies declined</li><li>Concept of&nbsp;<b>Samrat</b>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<b>Samrajya&nbsp;</b>came,&nbsp;<b>Monarchy&nbsp;</b>came</li><li>priests became important&nbsp;</li><li>Rajasuya sacrifices</li><li>Vajapeya; drink of strength&nbsp;sacrifices, ritual involved chariot race</li><li>Srauta sacrifices to control resources</li><li>sabha and samiti declined</li><li>janapada term came in this period</li><li>people lived in mud&nbsp;brick&nbsp;houses</li><li>nagara, meaning commercial quarters</li><li>Tribes</li><ol><li>kurus, panchalas, vashas, ushinaras</li><li>kurus and panchalas, became major group and made Hastinapur as capital</li><li>mention of mund words, indicates munda speaking people</li></ol></ol></div><div><br></div><div>Economic Life</div><div><ol><li>Later vedic period called Painted Gray Ware</li><li>other Black and Red ware</li><li>Black-Slipped Ware</li><li>Red Ware</li><li>mainly iron used, cleared forests</li><li>more settled life in later vedic period, surplus production&nbsp;</li><li>iron referred as Shyama Ayas or Dark Metal</li><li>new tools</li><li>cow dung as manure</li><li>number of cattle as estimate of Economic status</li><li>gold and silver coins swarna, satamana in use</li></ol></div><div><br></div><div>Social and Society</div><div><ol><li><b>Varna system</b></li><li>brahmanas: religious ceremonies</li><li>Kshatriyas or Rajanyas: waged wars</li><li>Vaishyas: traders</li><li>Sudras: menial works, not allowed to recite mantras, also no woman</li><li>emergence of gotra</li><li>crops barley, rice and wheat</li><li>sacrifices and rituals increased</li><li>ashwamedha yag, to mark the territory</li><li>Vajapeya involved chariot race</li><li>period marked by lineages of clans, small kingdoms in ganga valley</li></ol></div><div><br></div><div>Family<ol><li>more organised and male head, women only as wife and mother role</li><li>patriarchal family</li><li>polygamy emerged</li><li>married man with wife called as Yajamana</li><li>till now only Brahmacharya, Grihasta, Vanaprastha</li><li>Sanyasa developed later</li></ol><div>Status of Women</div></div><div><ol><li>no equal rights in later vedic period</li><li>role of mother and wife only</li><li>child marriage, polygamy</li><li>sati became prevalent</li></ol><div>Agriculture<ol><li>spread more, king also undertook activity</li><li>use of iron to clear more lands</li><li>Balarama as god with plough</li><li>barley, wheat, rice in ganga yamuna doab</li><li>more use of rice rather than wheat</li></ol><div>Craft Production<ol><li>more use of iron, bronze, copper</li><li>weaving by women</li><li>pottery, carpenter, leatherwork</li><li>Kulala means potters, Urna Sutra, wool</li><li>mention of elephant in Atharva veda</li><li>wealth estimate in terms of cattle</li></ol><div>Trade&nbsp;<ol><li>trade increased in later vedic period</li><li>no coins found, barter system</li><li>coins came after 600 BC</li></ol></div></div></div></div><div><br></div><div>Education</div><div><ol><li>brahmin in gurukuls</li><li>women gargi and maitreyi</li><li>teachings of upanishads, vedas, grammer, medicine</li><li>royal children's Dhanurvidya</li></ol></div><div><br></div><div>Religion in later vedic period</div><div><ol><li>varna dharma</li><li>vedic gods lost importance</li><li>prajapati, brahma, vishnu, rudra gained importance</li><li>faith in soul and moksha came into being</li><li>priests and meaningless rituals, sacrifices</li><li>rituals became complex and stress on correct performance of rituals</li><li>various rituals to solve day to day problems</li><li>these give rise to buddhism and jainism</li></ol><div>Philosophy<ol><li>literature, Philosophy, science developed in this period</li><li>teacher-pupil relationship developed</li><li>development of vedic texts, oral transmission</li><li>Aranyakas, priests who were in forest</li><li>Upanishads means to sit nearby , philosophical texts</li><li>Comes under Vedanta, means last part of vedic texts</li><li>stress atman, self realisation, Brahman, cycle of rebirth</li></ol><div>Other Aspects of Life<ol><li>evidence of music and fine arts</li><li>flute, drums</li><li>ornaments of metal, gold, copper</li><li>metal mirrors, glass beads</li></ol></div></div></div><div><br></div></div><div><br></div><div>Extra notes</div><div>Bali: 1/6th agriculture tax</div><div>Vedic Texts<br><ol><li><b><i>Shruti</i></b><ol><li>four vedas</li><li>aranyakas</li><li>brahmanas</li><li>upanishads</li></ol></li><li><b>Smriti</b><ol><li>puranas</li><li>ramayana</li><li>dharmasutra</li><li>manusmriti</li><li>narada smriti</li></ol></li></ol></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><img src="images/routes%20of%20aryans.JPG"></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div>Dravidians vs Aryans<ol><li>dark, medium height, long hair---fair, tall, brown hair</li><li>trade-----cattle rearing and war</li><li>cotton clothes---woolen, cotton, made out of skin</li><li>use of burnt bricks---use of bamboo</li><li>worshipped idols, lingam----no idol worship in rig veda, worshipped natural forces</li><li>&nbsp;copper---iron</li><li><b>tiger</b>---<b>horses</b></li><li>agriculture civilization, towns----cattle rearing, villages</li></ol><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div></div></div><div><br></div><div><div><span style="font-size: 16.8px;">IV.Match The Following</span></div><div><span style="font-size: 16.8px;">1. Satamana - <span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>Shiva</span></div><div><span style="font-size: 16.8px;">2. Praja - <span style="white-space: pre;">	</span><span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>Rajan&nbsp;</span></div><div><span style="font-size: 16.8px;">3. Rudra - </span><span style="font-size: 16.8px; white-space: pre;">	</span><span style="font-size: 16.8px; white-space: pre;">	</span><span style="font-size: 16.8px;">Vishwapati&nbsp;</span></div><div><span style="font-size: 16.8px;">4. HeadofJana - <span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>coins&nbsp;</span></div><div><span style="font-size: 16.8px;">5. Head of Visu - </span><span style="font-size: 16.8px; white-space: pre;">	</span><span style="font-size: 16.8px;">people of the&nbsp;kingdom</span></div></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div></div></div>
    </div>`}

    ,{ title: "Chapter 8 Rise of Kingdoms, Mauryan Empire ",content:`<input id="chapter" placeholder="Chapter" value="Chapter 8">
    <input class="subtitle" placeholder="Chapter Name" value="Rise of Kingdoms, Mauryan Empire">
    <div class="editor" contenteditable="true">
        <div><br></div><div><div><br></div><div><b>Dynasties</b></div><div><ol><li>Haryanka<ol><li>first buddha council</li></ol></li><li>Sisunaga<ol><li>2nd council</li></ol></li><li>Nalanda</li><li>Mauryan<ol><li>3rd council</li></ol></li><li>Sungas</li><li>Kanvas</li><li>Satavahanas<ol><li>metronyms</li></ol></li><li>Sakas</li><li>Kushan<ol><li>4th buddha council</li></ol></li><li>Gupta<ol><li>golden age</li><li>Chandragupta I, Samudragupta , Fahien&nbsp;during&nbsp;chandragupta II</li></ol></li><li>Harsha</li><ol><li>Hiuen-tsang</li></ol><li>Pallavas<ol><li>M1</li><li>N1</li><li>N2 or Rajasimha</li></ol></li><li>Chalukyas<ol><li>Pulakesin</li></ol></li><li>Rashtrakutas</li></ol><div>Extra Notes:</div><div><ol><li>Buddhist text, <b>Samannaphala Sutta</b>, while making a reference to Ajatashatru of Magadha met Gautama Buddha</li><li><b>Ajivikas</b></li><ol><li>a ascetic group, naked ascept&nbsp;</li><li>founder : Nanda Vachha</li><li>HQ: sravasti</li><li>principle: <b><i>niyati or fate</i></b></li><li>six inevitable factors:&nbsp;gain and loss, joy and sorrow, and life and death</li><li>spread to many areas but less than jainism and buddhism</li></ol><li><b>Lokyata</b> and Carvaka</li><ol><li>Lokayata means <b>materialist</b> thoughts</li><li>Carvaka: concept of scepticism , doubt, pursuit of knowledge through experience</li></ol><li>later vedic period, loyalty shifted from jana(clan or tribe) or janapada(territory)</li><li>bali, kara, shulk taxes</li><li>Grihapatis: landowners,owners, krishakas, smaller landowers</li></ol></div></div></div><div><br></div><div><b>Mahajanapadas</b></div><div><ol><li>janapadas fought among themselves</li><li>small janapadas joined to form mahajanapadas</li><li>16 Mahajanapadas mentioned in buddhist literature <b>Anguttara Nikaya</b></li><ol><li>Anga - champa<ol><li>modern bihar</li><li>merchant routes</li></ol></li><li><b style="">Magadha- rajgir&nbsp;</b><b>patliputra</b><b style="">&nbsp;bihar</b><ol><li>Haryanka Dynasty</li></ol></li><li><b style="">Kosala - Shravasti&nbsp;</b><b>ayodhya</b><b style="">&nbsp;eastern UP&nbsp;</b><ol><li>included Lumbini, birthplace of buddha</li></ol></li><li>Kashi - Varanasi</li><li>Vajji - Vaishali<ol><li>mahavira belonged to Jnatrikas clan</li></ol></li><li>Malla - Kusinara<ol><li>buddha took last meal</li></ol></li><li>Kedi</li><li><b style="">Vatsa - Kausambi, allahabad</b><ol><li>Udayana, hero of three dramas</li></ol></li><li>Kuru -&nbsp; Indraprastha<ol><li>mahabharata</li></ol></li><li>Panchala</li><li>Mastya</li><li>Surasena</li><li>Aswakas - Potali<ol><li>only kingdom south of Vindhyas</li></ol></li><li><b><i>Avanti-ujjain</i></b></li><li>Gandhara</li><li>Kamboj</li></ol></ol><div><i><img src="http://127.0.0.1:5500/images/location%20of%20mahajanpadas.JPG"></i></div><div><br></div><div>Why magadha rises?<ol><li>lower part of gangetic plain, agriculture yield</li><li>thick forest supplied timber, elephants</li><li>natural resources</li><li>growth of trade and commerce</li><li>Urbanization</li></ol></div><div><br></div><div><b style="">Haryanka Dynasty</b>-<b style="">Bimbisara: 546-494 BC</b><ol><li><b>Bimbisara - Ajatasatru - Udain</b></li><li>Area in bihar</li><li>capital: <b>siravasthi</b>, later <b>Rajgir</b>, and at last <b>Patliputra</b></li><li>Bimbisara: Haryanka Dynasty<ol><li>bimbisara extended territory by <b>matrimonial </b>alliances</li><li>3 marriages Lichchavis, Kosala, Punjab&nbsp;</li><li><b>friendly </b>relation with Avanti</li><li><b>annexed</b> weak states like Anga</li><li>contemporary of both<b> mahavira and buddha</b></li></ol></li><li><b>Ajatashatru 494-462</b><ol><li>imprisoned and killed his own father Bimbisara</li><li>military conquests, fought kosala, vaishali, Lichchavis</li><li>his main work <b>fortification of Patliputra</b></li><li>he also met buddha, scene depicted in sculptures of bharhut</li><li>constructed chaityas and viharas</li><li>First buddhist council immediately after death of Buddha</li></ol></li><li>Udain son of ajatashatru<ol><li>laid foundation of new capital at Pataliputra, modern Patna</li><li>strategic location of Patliputra</li></ol></li></ol><div><br></div><div><b>Sisunaga Dynasty - Mahapadma Nanda</b><ol><li>sisunaga defeated Haryanka</li><li>capital: Rajgir, later Patliputra</li><li>temporary shifted capital to Vaishali</li><li>important achievement: defeat of Avanti and make it part of Magadha</li><li>period is not clear</li><li>as empire began to collapse, <b>Kalashoka </b>ascended throne<ol><li><b>shifted capital from rajagriha to pataliputra</b></li><li>2nd buddha council vaishali 383 BC</li></ol></li></ol></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><b><i>Nanda Dynasty - Mahapadma Nanda 345-321 BC</i></b><ol><li>Fame of magadh scaled new heights under nandas, the empire builders</li><li>Non Kshatriyas Clan, theory that Mahapadma nanda son of Shudra woman</li><li>they were Sudras</li><li><b><i>Mahapadma Nanda</i></b><ol><li>&nbsp;first king, title Ekarat</li><li>defeated kshatriyas</li><li>extended magadha empire beyond vindhyas to deccan, empire builder</li><li><b>Hathigumpha inscription of kharavela of kalinga refers to conquest of kalinga by Nandas</b></li></ol></li><li>Patronized jainism</li><li>short rule 10 years</li><li>Dhana Nanda<ol><li>he was oppressive, resented by people</li><li>imposed heavy taxes</li><li>invented Nandopakramani, measuring standard</li><li><i><b>alexander</b> fought with porus,during his reign</i></li><li>CGM defeated Dhana Nanda</li></ol></li></ol><div><br></div><div>Notes on King of kharavela<ol><li>1st century</li><li>Hathigumpha inscription, situated in Udayagiri Hills, Orissa</li><li>followers of jainism</li><li>hathigumpha evidence of jainism in orissa</li></ol></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><b><i>Persian and Greek Invasions</i></b><ol><li><b>Cysur 558-530 BC</b></li><ol><li><span>cyrus of Achaemenid&nbsp;Empire first conqueror who led invasion in india</span></li><li><span>capture gandhara region</span></li><li><span>gandhara and indus region were part of Achaemenid&nbsp;Empire of persia</span></li></ol><li><b>Darius I 522-486 BC</b></li><ol><li>grandson of cyrus conquered indus valley</li><li>mention of word 'Hindu' in inscription, hindu refer to as indian part</li><li>mention of sindhu denoting river</li></ol><li><b>Xerxes&nbsp; 465-456 BC</b></li><li><b>Effects of persian invasion</b><ol><li>growth of indo-iranian commerce</li><li>prepared ground for alexander's invasion</li><li>indo-greeks first rulers to issue coins, gold, silver, copper, nickel</li><li>their coins in attic weight standard, with greek gods</li><li>coins in indian side in bilingual, greek, kharosthi</li><li><b>kharosthi </b>script,right to left, used by Ashoka in inscriptions, in Gandhara region</li><li>effect on Gandhara art</li><li>also affected Mauryan art and architecture, bell shaped of Sarnath</li></ol></li><li><span><b>Alexander’s Invasion of India (327-325 B.C.)</b><ol><li>alexander of macedonia invaded india</li><li>in north western parts, leading kings at that time: Ambhi of taxila</li><li>ambhi of taxila accept his suzerainty</li><li><b style="font-style: italic;">Porus ruled between jhelum and chenab&nbsp;</b></li><li>alexander easily overcame rulers</li><li>Causes of invasion</li><ol><li>attracted by wealth of india</li><li>interest in geographical and love for nature</li><li>he believed that eastern side of india , continuation of sea</li><li>so he thought after india, he would get to conqueror whole east</li></ol><li>Showdown <b><i>Battle of Hydaspes Porus vs Alexander</i></b></li><ol><li>&nbsp;alexander crossed hindu kush mountains, crossed indus river</li><li>received by ambhi, the ruler of taxila,&nbsp;</li><li>alex sent message to porus, but porus decided to fight</li><li>alex had to cross river Hydaspes: Jhelum , on other side fought with porus</li><li>fight on plains of <b>karri</b>, porus lost</li><li>alex reinstated him on his throne</li></ol><li>later alex wanted to go further but his soldiers refused</li></ol></span></li><li>after alex invasion</li><ol><li>encouraged unification of india under mauryas</li><li>direct contact between india and greece, trade also flourished</li><li>after alex , mauryas rises under CGM</li><li>north west part of india became centre of confluence of persian and indian culture</li><li>Gandhara art heavily influenced by persian art, buddha figures</li><li>Edicts here are in kharosthi script, written right to left</li><li>influence in ashoka pillar sarnath, bell shaped lotus</li></ol><li>Taxila<ol><li>in pakistan region was part of Achaemenid&nbsp;Empire</li><li>due to strategic location on trade route became important centre of learning and culture</li><li>1940s by John Marshall</li><li>panni, compiled Ashtadhyayi here</li></ol></li></ol></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><b><i>MAURYAN EMPIRE</i></b></div><div><div><span><b><i><br></i></b></span></div><div><span><b><i>SOURCES</i></b></span></div><div><ol><li><b><i>Kautilya wrote Arthashastra</i></b>&nbsp;in sanskrit, first discovered by R.S Sastri 1904<ol><li>literal meaning: science of statecraft</li><li>it contains 3 parts, 15 books and 180 chapters</li><li>1st part: king and council</li><li>2nd: civil and criminal law</li><li>3rd diplomacy and war</li></ol></li><li><b><i>Vishakhadatta&nbsp;Mudrarakshasa</i></b>, sanskrit written in gupta period, a play describes how kautilya helped CGM to overthrow Nandas<ol><li>it describes how CGM with kautilya overthrew nandas</li></ol></li><li>Hemachandra's Parishishta Parvan, tells about CGM relation with Jainism</li><li>Dandin's Dashakumaracharita</li><li>Banabhatta's kadambari</li><li>Megasthenes' Indica, greek ambassador of nicator</li><li><b><i>Others: jatkas, ceylonese chronicles, dipavamsa, mahavamsa</i></b>&nbsp;tells about Ashoka spreading&nbsp;buddhism</li><li>Inscription of <b>junagadh</b>, near Girnar, gujarat<ol><li>tells about extent of mauryan empire upto gujarat</li><li>name of CGM even after 400 years</li></ol></li><li>Edicts of Ashoka<ol><li>deciphered brahmi script at sanchi by james prinsep 1837</li><li>refer to ashoka as Devanampriya, piyadassi</li><li>puranic and buddhist texts refer to ashoka as Chakravartin</li><li>kharosthi: north west</li><li>pali, prakrit, , brahmi script for writing</li><li>13: kalinga</li><li>2: dhamma</li><li>7: promote dhamma</li></ol></li></ol></div><div><br></div><div><b><i>CGM 322-298 BC</i></b></div><div><ol><li>chandragupta maurya started mauryan empire by defeated&nbsp;<b>dhanananda</b></li><li>took over empire BC 324-299</li><li><b><i>seleucus nicator&nbsp;</i></b>came to fight with CGM</li><ol><li>cgm won, he sent 500 elephants to nicator</li><li>nicator gave his daughter to CGM</li><li><b>megasthenes&nbsp;</b>, ambassador of seleucus came to CGM court</li><li>he wrote Indica book, lived for 14 years in india</li></ol><li>Later CGM followed&nbsp;<b>jainism</b>, with bhadrabahu he went to south shravanabelagola</li><li>their CGM performed&nbsp;Sallekhana&nbsp;</li><li><b><i>Kautilya’s&nbsp;</i></b>Arthashastra</li><li><b><i>Vishakhadatta&nbsp;</i></b>Mudrarakshasa&nbsp;</li></ol></div><div><br></div><div><b><i>BINDUSARA 298-273 BC</i></b></div><div><ol><li>Amitraghata- slayer of enemies</li><li>Appointed&nbsp;&nbsp;<b><i>Ashoka as governor of Ujjain</i></b></li><li>conquered land between two seas, upto mysore</li><li>he also got Deimachus as ambassador from Syrian King Antiochus I</li><li>he also asked for wine, dried figs, a sophist, Antiochus sent all but sophist</li><li>supported ajivikas, a religious sect</li></ol></div><div><br></div><div><span><b><i>ASHOKA 273-232 BC</i></b></span></div><div><ol><li>after CGM, bindusara</li><li>ashoka grandson of CGM</li><li>suppressed revolt a taxila when he was governor of ujjain</li><li>first 4 years spent to suppress his brothers</li><li>after kalinga war 261 BC, ashoka followed buddhism under monk <b>Nigrodha</b></li><ol><li>gradual conversion to buddhism</li><li>followed dharma vijaya,&nbsp;spread dharma through rock edicts</li><li>first became upasaka, disciple , 2 years later became Bikshu</li><li>visited bodh gaya and organised mission</li><li>ashoka appointed Dhamma-mahamattas to spread dhamma</li><li>under ashoka 3rd buddha council at pataliputra,&nbsp;<b><i>tissa&nbsp;</i></b>participated</li><li>his son mahendra spread dharma in ceylon</li></ol><li>Total 33 edicts,&nbsp;<b><i>14 major</i></b>, 2 kalinga edicts, 7 pillar edicts</li><ol><li>Language: brahmi, magadhi, prakrit script, kharosthi, kandahar&nbsp;region in greek and aramaic</li><li>Edict <b>1</b>: prohibit animal sacrifice</li><li><i>Edict </i><b style="">2</b><i>: dhamma explained ,</i>mention of&nbsp;<b>cholas</b>,&nbsp;<b>pandyas</b>, setup of hospitals in state</li><li>Edict <b style="font-style: italic;">3:</b>&nbsp;tour every 5 years to check if instructions are being carried out</li><li>Edict <b>5</b>: Dhamma-mahamattas to spread dhamma</li><li>Edict <b style="font-style: italic;">6</b>: ruler should be informed about his kingdom</li><li>Edict&nbsp;<b style="font-style: italic;">7:&nbsp;</b>religions should coexist and honoured, mention of <b>cholas</b>, pandyas</li><li>Edict <b>8</b>: royal pleasure tours</li><li>Edict <b>9</b>: criticizes useless ceremonies, lay stress on dhamma</li><li>Edict <b>10</b>:&nbsp; king desires no fame or glory</li><li>Edict <b>11</b>: policy of dhamma</li><li>Edict <b>13</b>: describes kalinga war 261 BC, digvijay replaced by Dhamma Vijay</li><li>Edict <b>14</b>: purpose of rock edicts</li></ol><li>Feroz shah tughlaq shifted pillars from meerut to delhi</li><li>Pillars Features<ol><li>monolithic, sandstone</li><li>without base 12-14 meter height</li><li>lotus, lions, bull, elephant</li></ol></li><li>Important Edicts<ol><li>Allahabad</li><ol><li>queen's edict</li><li>also mention of Samudragupta&nbsp;</li></ol><li>Girnar, inscription of Rudraman</li><ol><li>mention of sudarshan lake built by pushya gupta</li></ol><li>Kandahar inscription</li><ol><li>bilingual greek, aramaic</li></ol><li>Nighali Sagar, Nepal</li><ol><li>ashoka visited here</li></ol><li>Rummindei Nepal</li><ol><li>birthplace of buddha, ashoke visited lumbini</li></ol><li>Sannati inscription, karnataka</li><ol><li>14 major rock edicts</li></ol><li>Kalinga Edict</li><ol><li>mentions all men are my children</li></ol><li>Sohgaura Copper Plate</li><ol><li><b>relief</b> measures adopted during famine</li></ol><li>Shahbazgarhi and Mansehra in kharosthi language</li></ol></li><li>Barbara caves gifted to Ajivikas</li><li>stupas at sarnath, lumbini</li><li>highly polished stupa at sanchi</li><li>edicts written in Prakrit, kharosthi, brahmi script</li></ol></div><ol><li>Ashoka's Dhamma<ol><li>a broad concept containing moral values</li><li>service to parents, ahimsa, love of truth, humane treatment of servants etc</li><li>he did not equate dhamma with buddhist teachings</li><li>dhamma was general code and buddhism his personal belief</li></ol></li><li><b>Administration of Empire</b></li><ol><li>monarch rule, king assisted by council of ministers</li><li>purohita, mahamantri, senapati, yuvraha</li><li>all can be considered civil servants: Amatyas, a well organised administration</li><li>divided into 5 provinces</li><ol><li>north: taxila</li><li>west: ujjain, malwa</li><li>south: swarnagiri, kurnool AP</li><li>east: dosali, kalinga</li><li>main: magadha ruler by king, capital: Patliputra</li></ol><li>Mahamatras as <b><i>governors </i></b>for provinces</li><li><b><i>Rajukas</i></b>, officer similar to collector</li><li><b><i>Sthanika</i></b>, head of district</li><li><b><i>Gopa</i></b> head of 10-15 villages</li><li><b style="font-style: italic;">Gramini </b>head of Village, villages semi-autonomous</li><li>municipal administration under Nagarika&nbsp;</li></ol><li>City of Patliputra<ol><li>14 km length and 2.5km wide</li><li>64 gates and 570 watch towers</li></ol></li><li>Revenue system</li><ol><li><b>Samaharta</b>: chief of Revenue dept.</li><li>bali and bagha tax 1/6th of produce</li></ol><li>Army</li><ol><li>cash payments</li><li>megasthenes mention 6 boards of 5 members each to control 6 wings of military</li><li>navy, infantry, transport, supply</li></ol><li>Judicial and Police</li><ol><li>&nbsp;dharmasthiya courts, kantaka shodhana courts,&nbsp; civil and criminal courts</li><li>provincial and district courts under <b><i>Amatyas</i></b></li><li>police centres, jails, remission of unjust sentences&nbsp;</li></ol><li>Census<ol><li>regular census, including animals</li><li>by municipal officials, census was permanent administration</li></ol></li><li>Currency</li><ol><li>silver coins symbol <b>peacock</b></li><li>copper coins Mashakas, <b>Panna </b>in use</li></ol><li>Art and architecture<ol><li><b><i>Statues </i></b>of yakshas and yakshis<ol><li><b><i>Yakshas were deities </i></b>connected with water, fertility, trees, the forest and wilderness.</li><li>Yakshas&nbsp;were their female counterpart</li></ol></li><li><span><b>Stupa of Sanchi</b></span></li><li><span><b><i>Pillars</i></b>:<b> Sarnath Pillar by ashoka</b><i><ol><li>4 lions statue , adopted by indian govt. as state emblem</li></ol></i></span></li><li><span><b>Caves</b><ol><li>caves of barabar hills new bodh gaya</li><li>interior is polished like mirror</li></ol></span></li><li><div>Silk was known referred to chinese silk</div></li><li><div>Craftsmen under royal workshops<ol><li>head pramukha and jetha or jyeshta</li></ol></div></li></ol></li><li>Later Mauryas<br><ol><li>ashoka died in 232 BC, empire division into two east and west</li><li>last ruler Brihadratha, killed by pushyamitra, started sunga dynasty</li></ol></li></ol><div><span>III.Match the following.&nbsp;</span></div><div><span>1.Dharma Mahamatras<span>	</span></span><span>a) Village administration&nbsp;</span></div><div><span>2.Gopa<span>	</span><span>	</span><span>	</span><span>	<span>	</span></span>b) Revenue administration&nbsp;</span></div><div><span>3.Nagarika<span>	</span><span>	</span><span>	<span>	</span></span>c) Spread of Dhamma&nbsp;</span></div><div><span>4.Samharta<span>	</span><span>	</span><span>	<span>	</span></span>d) City administration&nbsp;</span></div></div></div></div><div><br></div><div>Edicts of ashoka</div><div><img src="http://127.0.0.1:5500/images/edicts%20of%20ashoka.JPG"></div><div><br></div><div>Mauryan empire</div><div><img src="http://127.0.0.1:5500/images/mauryan%20empire.JPG"></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><div><div><div><div><div><br></div></div></div><div><br></div><div><br></div></div><div><br></div><div><br></div></div></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div></div>
    </div>`}



    ,{ title: "Chapter 5 Sangam Age ",content:`<input id="chapter" placeholder="Chapter" value="Chapter 5">
    <span>	</span><input class="subtitle" placeholder="Chapter Name" value="Sangam Age">
    <div class="editor" contenteditable="true">
        <div>NOTES</div><div><ol><li>There were 3 Sangams (academy of Tamil Poets)</li><li>Nannool book by Bavandhi Munivar</li><li><b>Sangam</b> refers to the association of poets who flourished under the royal patronage of the Pandya kings at Madurai</li></ol><div><br></div></div><div><b>Three Sangams 3rd BC to 3rd AD &gt; Muchchangam</b><ol><li>flourished under royal patronage of pandyas</li><li><span><b>Muvendar </b>refer to , ‘the three crowned kings’, the Cheras, the Cholas and the Pandyas&nbsp;</span></li><li><b>First </b>sangam: no records, attended by gods</li><li><b>Second </b>sangam: Kapadapuram, source: Tolkappiyam by Tholkappiyar</li><li><b>Third </b>sangam: attended by poets, literature survived</li><li><b>Literature</b><ol><li><b>Tolkappiyam by Tholkappiyar</b>, a tamil grammar book</li><li><b>Ettuthogai</b>: <b>8</b> works, Aham(love) and puram(valour)</li><li><b>Pathupattu</b>: <b>10</b> idylls</li><li><b>Pathinenkilkanakku</b>: <b>18</b> works, ethics and morals</li><li><b>Sillappathigaam </b>by Elango Adigal(cheras)</li><li><b>Manimegalai</b> by Seethalai Sathanar</li><li>Dipavamsa, Mahavamsa chronicles of Buddhism</li><li>Ashoka's inscription also mentions chera, chola, pandya in 2nd pillar</li><li>Hathigumpha inscription of kharavela of kalinga mentions tamil kingdoms</li><li>Roman coins of 1st century at various places of tamil</li></ol></li></ol><div><br></div><div><b>Cheras</b>: 🏹</div><ol><ol><li>Capital:&nbsp;<b>VANJI, KERALA</b></li><li>Region: <ol><li>central and northern part of <b>Kerala</b></li><li>Kongu region of <b>tamil nadu</b></li><li>Cochin, South Malabar&nbsp;</li></ol></li><li><span>Titles: Vanavan, <b style="">Kuttuvan</b>, Irumporai and Villavar</span></li><li><b style="">Tondi and Musiri</b> Seaports</li><li><b>Pathitrupathu&nbsp;</b>: Ten poems, mention of 8 Chera kings</li><li>Pugalur inscription of tamil nadu 1st century refers to 3 generations of chera rulers</li><li><b>Cheran</b> <b>Senguttuvan </b>famous ruler</li><ol><li>of 2nd century AD</li><li>his brother <b>Elango Adigal </b>wrote <b>Silapathikaram</b></li><li><b>pattini cult</b> or worship of <b>kannagi </b>as ideal wife</li><li>stone for worship brought by him from himalaya</li></ol><li>Coins: copper and lean, imitating roman coins</li></ol></ol><div><br></div><div><b>Cholas: 🐅</b></div><ol><ol><li>Region: <ol><li>central and northern parts of TN</li><li>core area kaveri delta, later called Cholamandalam</li></ol></li><li>capital: <b>Uraiyur, later Puhar&nbsp;</b></li><li><i>Titles of king:&nbsp;</i><span><i>Senni, Valavan and Killi&nbsp;</i></span></li><li><i style=""><span>Kaveripattinam&nbsp;attracted merchants</span></i></li><li><i style=""><span>Pattinappalai, by Katiyalur, description of trade in town</span></i></li><li><b>KARIKALA</b></li><ol><li>Battle of Venni he defeated cheras, pandyas and 11 minor rulers</li><li>account rule in Pattinappalai</li><li>he converted forest into habitable region, developed agriculture</li><li>reservoirs at embakment of Kaveri</li><li>Vahaipparandalai another battle fought by him</li><li>overload of whole tamil region</li><li>he built Kallani across Kaveri river</li></ol><li>Perunnalkili, another ruler performed Vedic Sacrifice Rajasuyam</li></ol><li>Pandyas: 🐟</li><ol><li>region: southern Tamil Nadu, Madurai</li><li>capital: <b>Madurai&nbsp;</b></li><li><i>Titles of king:&nbsp;</i><i style=""><span>Minavar</span></i></li><li><i>famous for pearl fishery and chank diving</i></li><li><span><b style="">Ne</b></span><b style="">dunchezhiyan I</b><ol><li>defeated aryans</li><li>killed Kovalan, for which <b>Kannagi </b>burnt madurai</li><li>he died of remorse, after execution of Kovalan</li></ol></li><li><span><b>Ne</b><b>dunchezhiyan II</b>&nbsp;</span><br></li><ol><li>battle of Talaiyalanganam</li><li><b>nedunchezhiyan </b>defeated combined army of chera and chola</li></ol><li><span>Madurai Kanji&nbsp;written by Mangudi Maruthanar describes the socio-economic condition</span></li><li><span>seaport: <b>Korkai</b></span></li><li>known for pearl hunting and chank diving</li><li>coins: one side Elephant and Fish</li><li><span>later sangam age declined due to invasion of <b><i>Kalabhras</i></b> .</span></li></ol><li>Polity<ol><li>hereditary monarchy</li><li>king advised by officials divided into 5 councils</li><ol><li>ministers</li><li>priests</li><li>military commander</li><li>Envoys</li><li>Spies</li></ol><li>highly efficient organised military administration</li><li>land revenue, custom duty were part of state income</li><li>Pattinappalai, custom officials at sea ports</li><li>well maintained roads, with guards to prevent robbery</li></ol></li><li>Society<br></li><ol><li>Tolkappiyam refers to 5 fold division of society</li><li>Kurinchi:🌄🌋🗻<ol><li>mountains or hilly tracks,&nbsp;</li><li>deity: Murugan,</li><li>hunting and&nbsp; honey collection</li></ol></li><li>mullai:🏝🏕🏞🏜🛤<ol><li>pastoral area</li><li>vishnu</li><li>cattle rearing, dairy products</li></ol></li><li>Neidel:🏖🌊🌊🌊🌊<ol><li>coastal areas</li><li>Varuna</li><li>fishing and salt making</li></ol></li><li>palai:🏜🏜🏜🏜🏜🏜🏜🏜🏜<ol><li>desert or Sandy area</li><li>korravai</li><li>robbery, thiefs</li></ol></li><li><span>Marutham👩‍🌾👩‍🌾👩‍🌾👩‍🌾👩‍🌾👩‍🌾<ol><li>the cultivable land</li><li>indira</li><li>agriculture</li></ol></span></li><li>Also 4 cast system</li><ol><li>Arasar: ruling</li><li>Anthana: priests</li><li>Vanigar: trade, commerce</li><li>Vellalar: agriculturists</li></ol><li>although traditional cast system but all enjoyed respect</li></ol><li><b>Administration</b><ol><li>Political Class<ol><li>Kizhar: head of nadu, nadu is group of villages</li><li>Velir: territory varied geographical areas</li><li>Vendar: kings controlling large area</li></ol></li><li>kingdom:&nbsp;<i><b>Mandalam&gt;nadus&gt;</b><span><b>kurram</b></span><b>&gt;ur</b></i></li><li>mandalam into nadus: nadus headed by Kizhar</li><li>nadus into kurram</li><li>kurram into villages</li><li>villages<ol><li>Ur village</li><li>Sirur: small village</li><li>mudur: old village</li></ol></li></ol></li><li>Religion</li><ol><li>deity: Murugan, tamil god</li><li>other gods Mayon, Vendana, Varuna, Korravai</li><li>Hero stone or Nadu Kal worship</li><li>asvamedha sacrifices shows&nbsp; vedic culture</li><li>presence of buddhism, brahmanism, jainism</li></ol><li>Women</li><ol><li>women were not equal with men</li><li>women poets flourished, also active in economic production</li><li>love marriage common</li><li><b>widows miserable, practice of Sati</b></li><li>dancing patronized by kings</li></ol><li>Arts</li><ol><li><span>Poetry, music and dancing were popular&nbsp;</span></li><li><span>royals courts had singing bards like Panar, Viraliyar</span></li><li><span>Koothu was popular&nbsp;</span>artists play songs with dance and music in storytelling the epics</li></ol><li>Economy</li><ol><li>chief occupation agriculture</li><li>rice, ragi, sugarcane, cotton, pepper, ginger, turmeric, cinnamon</li><li>jackfruit and pepper&nbsp;</li><li>paddy crop famous in chola and pandya</li><li>industry metal works, carpentry, ship building, ornaments, beads, stones, ivory</li><li>mention of cotton clothes as thin as a cloud of steam or a slough of snake</li><li>internal and external trade well organised</li><li>port city of Puhar in tamil nadu trade with romans</li><li>gold and silver coins of romans found in tamil regions</li><li>main exports: cotton, spices, ginger, cinnamon</li><li>import: turmeric, ivory, pearls, gold, sweet wine</li><li>roman gold coins found in coimbatore</li><li>chattu: refer to itinerary of merchants</li><li>barter system and coins both</li></ol><li>Decline<ol><li>Kalabhras invasion<ol><li>period form 300 to 600 AD</li><li>impression evil rule, war like group</li></ol></li><li>later Jainism and Buddhism came</li></ol></li></ol><div><br></div><div>Lemuria continent</div><div><ol><li>big landmass connecting africa and australia called as Lemuria</li></ol><div><br></div><div><div><span>Match the following:</span></div><div><span>1. Tolkappiyam&nbsp;- <span>	<span>	</span><span>	</span><span>	</span></span>Yano Arrasan;YanaeKalvan</span></div><div><span>2. Mullai - <span>	</span><span>	</span><span>	</span><span>	<span>	</span></span>Hero Stones 4</span></div><div><span>3. Pandiyar Nedunchezhiyan&nbsp;-<span>	</span>Ravi</span></div><div><span>4. Heroicdeath -&nbsp;<span>	</span><span>	</span><span>	</span><span>	</span>Coastal area 6</span></div><div><span>5. Kurinchi - <span>	</span><span>	</span><span>	</span><span>	</span><span>	</span>Book before Tamil&nbsp;Sangam 1</span></div><div><span>6. Neithel - <span>	</span><span>	</span><span>	</span><span>	</span><span>	</span>Forest area 2</span></div></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><img src="http://127.0.0.1:5500/images/sangam%20age.JPG"></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div></div></div>
    </div>`}

    ,{ title: "Chapter 8 Rise of Kingdoms, Mauryan Empire ",content:`<input id="chapter" placeholder="Chapter" value="Chapter 8">
    <input class="subtitle" placeholder="Chapter Name" value="Rise of Kingdoms, Mauryan Empire">
    <div class="editor" contenteditable="true">
        <div><br></div><div><div><br></div><div>Dynasties</div><div><ol><li>Haryanka<ol><li>first buddha council</li></ol></li><li>Sisunaga<ol><li>2nd council</li></ol></li><li>Nalanda</li><li><b style="font-style: italic;">Mauryan</b><ol><li>3rd council</li></ol></li><li>Sungas</li><li>Kanvas</li><li>Satavahanas</li><li>Sakas</li><li>Kushan<ol><li>4th buddha council</li></ol></li><li>Gupta<ol><li>golden age</li><li>Chandragupta I, Samudragupta , Fahien&nbsp;during&nbsp;chandragupta II</li></ol></li><li>Harsha</li><ol><li>Hiuen-tsang</li></ol><li>Pallavas</li><li>Chalukyas</li><li>Rashtrakutas</li></ol><div>Extra Notes:</div><div><ol><li>Buddhist text, <b><i>Samannaphala Sutta</i></b>, while making a reference to Ajatashatru of Magadha met Gautama Buddha</li><li>Ajivikas</li><ol><li>a ascetic group, naked ascept&nbsp;</li><li>founder : Nanda Vachha</li><li>HQ: sravasti</li><li>principle: <b><i>niyati or fate</i></b></li><li>six inevitable factors:&nbsp;gain and loss, joy and sorrow, and life and death</li><li><b>spread to many areas but less than jainism and buddhism</b></li></ol><li>Lokyata and Carvaka</li><ol><li>Lokayata means materialist thoughts</li><li>Carvaka: concept of scepticism , doubt, pursuit of knowledge through experience</li></ol><li>later vedic period, loyalty shifted from jana(clan or tribe) or janapada(territory)</li><li>bali, kara, shulk taxes</li><li>Grihapatis: landowners,owners, krishakas, smaller landowers</li></ol></div></div></div><div><br></div><div><b><i>Mahajanapadas</i></b></div><div><ol><li>janapadas fought among themselves</li><li>small janapadas joined to form mahajanapadas</li><li>16 Mahajanapadas mentioned in buddhist literature <b><i>Anguttara Nikaya</i></b></li><ol><li>Anga - champa<ol><li>capital: champa</li><li>modern bihar</li><li>merchant routes</li></ol></li><li><i style=""><b>Magadha- rajgir&nbsp;</b><span style="font-size: 16.8px; -webkit-text-fill-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"><b>patliputra</b></span><b>&nbsp;bihar</b><ol><li>Haryanka Dynasty</li></ol></i></li><li><b style="font-style: italic;">Kosala - Shravasti&nbsp;</b><span style="font-style: italic; font-size: 16.8px; -webkit-text-fill-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"><b>ayodhya</b></span><b style="font-style: italic;">&nbsp;eastern UP&nbsp;</b><ol><li>included Lumbini, birthplace of buddha</li></ol></li><li>Kashi - Varanasi</li><li>Vajji - Vaishali<ol><li>mahavira belonged to Jnatrikas clan</li></ol></li><li>Malla - Kusinara<ol><li>buddha took last meal</li></ol></li><li>Kedi</li><li><i style=""><b>Vatsa - Kausambi, allahabad </b>g<ol><li>Udayana, hero of three dramas</li></ol></i></li><li>Kuru -&nbsp; Indraprastha<ol><li>mahabharata</li></ol></li><li>Panchala</li><li>Mastya</li><li>Surasena</li><li>Aswakas - Potali<ol><li>only kingdom south of Vindhyas</li></ol></li><li><b><i>Avanti-ujjain</i></b></li><li>Gandhara</li><li>Kamboj</li></ol></ol><div style="text-align: left;"><i><img src="http://127.0.0.1:5500/images/location%20of%20mahajanpadas.JPG"></i></div><div><br></div><div>Why magadha rises?<ol><li>lower part of gangetic plain, agriculture yield</li><li>thick forest supplied timber, elephants</li><li>natural resources</li><li>growth of trade and commerce</li><li>urbanization</li></ol></div><div><br></div><div><b><i>Haryanka Dynasty</i></b>-&nbsp;<b><i>Bimbisara: 546-494 BC</i></b><ol><li><b><i>Bimbisara - Ajatasatru - Udain</i></b></li><li>Area in bihar</li><li>capital: <b>siravasthi</b>, later <b>Rajgir</b>, and at last <b>Patliputra</b></li><li>Bimbisara: Haryanka Dynasty<ol><li>bimbisara extended territory by <b>matrimonial </b>alliances</li><li>3 marriages Lichchavis, Kosala, Punjab&nbsp;</li><li><b>friendly </b>relation with Avanti</li><li><b>annexed</b> weak states like Anga</li><li>contemporary of both<b> mahavira and buddha</b></li></ol></li><li><b><i>Ajatashatru 494-462</i></b><ol><li>imprisoned and killed his own father Bimbisara</li><li>military conquests, fought kosala, vaishali, Lichchavis</li><li>his main work <b><i>fortification of Patliputra</i></b></li><li>he also met buddha, scene depicted in sculptures of bharhut</li><li>constructed chaityas and viharas</li><li>First buddhist council immediately after death of Buddha</li></ol></li><li>Udain son of ajatashatru<ol><li>laid foundation of new capital at Pataliputra, modern Patna</li><li>strategic location of Patliputra</li></ol></li></ol><div><br></div><div><b><i>Sisunaga Dynasty - Mahapadma Nanda</i></b><ol><li>sisunaga defeated Haryanka</li><li>capital: Rajgir, later Patliputra</li><li>temporary shifted capital to Vaishali</li><li>important achievement: defeat of Avanti and make it part of Magadha</li><li>period is not clear</li><li>as empire began to collapse, <b>Kalashoka </b>ascended throne<ol><li><b>shifted capital from rajagriha to pataliputra</b></li><li>2nd buddha council vaishali 383 BC</li></ol></li></ol></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><b><i>Nanda Dynasty - Mahapadma Nanda 345-321 BC</i></b><ol><li>Fame of magadh scaled new heights under nandas, the empire builders</li><li>Non Kshatriyas Clan, theory that Mahapadma nanda son of Shudra woman</li><li>they were Sudras</li><li><b><i>Mahapadma Nanda</i></b><ol><li>&nbsp;first king, title Ekarat</li><li>defeated kshatriyas</li><li>extended magadha empire beyond vindhyas to deccan, empire builder</li><li><b>Hathigumpha inscription of kharavela of kalinga refers to conquest of kalinga by Nandas</b></li></ol></li><li>Patronized jainism</li><li>short rule 10 years</li><li>Dhana Nanda<ol><li>he was oppressive, resented by people</li><li>imposed heavy taxes</li><li>invented Nandopakramani, measuring standard</li><li><i><b>alexander</b> fought with porus,during his reign</i></li><li>CGM defeated Dhana Nanda</li></ol></li></ol><div><br></div><div>Notes on King of kharavela<ol><li>1st century</li><li>Hathigumpha inscription, situated in Udayagiri Hills, Orissa</li><li>followers of jainism</li><li>hathigumpha evidence of jainism in orissa</li></ol></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><b><i>Persian and Greek Invasions</i></b><ol><li><b>Cysur 558-530 BC</b></li><ol><li><span style="font-size: 16.8px;">cyrus of Achaemenid&nbsp;Empire first conqueror who led invasion in india</span></li><li><span style="font-size: 16.8px;">capture gandhara region</span></li><li><span style="font-size: 16.8px;">gandhara and indus region were part of Achaemenid&nbsp;Empire of persia</span></li></ol><li><b>Darius I 522-486 BC</b></li><ol><li>grandson of cyrus conquered indus valley</li><li>mention of word 'Hindu' in inscription, hindu refer to as indian part</li><li>mention of sindhu denoting river</li></ol><li><b>Xerxes&nbsp; 465-456 BC</b></li><li><b>Effects of persian invasion</b><ol><li>growth of indo-iranian commerce</li><li>prepared ground for alexander's invasion</li><li>indo-greeks first rulers to issue coins, gold, silver, copper, nickel</li><li>their coins in attic weight standard, with greek gods</li><li>coins in indian side in bilingual, greek, kharosthi</li><li><b>kharosthi </b>script,right to left, used by Ashoka in inscriptions, in Gandhara region</li><li>effect on Gandhara art</li><li>also affected Mauryan art and architecture, bell shaped of Sarnath</li></ol></li><li><span style="font-size: 16.8px;"><b>Alexander’s Invasion of India (327-325 B.C.)</b><ol><li>alexander of macedonia invaded india</li><li>in north western parts, leading kings at that time: Ambhi of taxila</li><li>ambhi of taxila accept his suzerainty</li><li><b style="font-style: italic;">Porus ruled between jhelum and chenab&nbsp;</b></li><li>alexander easily overcame rulers</li><li>Causes of invasion</li><ol><li>attracted by wealth of india</li><li>interest in geographical and love for nature</li><li>he believed that eastern side of india , continuation of sea</li><li>so he thought after india, he would get to conqueror whole east</li></ol><li>Showdown <b><i>Battle of Hydaspes Porus vs Alexander</i></b></li><ol><li>&nbsp;alexander crossed hindu kush mountains, crossed indus river</li><li>received by ambhi, the ruler of taxila,&nbsp;</li><li>alex sent message to porus, but porus decided to fight</li><li>alex had to cross river Hydaspes: Jhelum , on other side fought with porus</li><li>fight on plains of <b>karri</b>, porus lost</li><li>alex reinstated him on his throne</li></ol><li>later alex wanted to go further but his soldiers refused</li></ol></span></li><li>after alex invasion</li><ol><li>encouraged unification of india under mauryas</li><li>direct contact between india and greece, trade also flourished</li><li>after alex , mauryas rises under CGM</li><li>north west part of india became centre of confluence of persian and indian culture</li><li>Gandhara art heavily influenced by persian art, buddha figures</li><li>Edicts here are in kharosthi script, written right to left</li><li>influence in ashoka pillar sarnath, bell shaped lotus</li></ol><li>Taxila<ol><li>in pakistan region was part of Achaemenid&nbsp;Empire</li><li>due to strategic location on trade route became important centre of learning and culture</li><li>1940s by John Marshall</li><li>panni, compiled Ashtadhyayi here</li></ol></li></ol></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><b><i>MAURYAN EMPIRE</i></b></div><div><div><span style="-webkit-text-fill-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"><b><i><br></i></b></span></div><div><span style="-webkit-text-fill-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"><b><i>SOURCES</i></b></span></div><div><ol><li><b><i>Kautilya wrote Arthashastra</i></b>&nbsp;in sanskrit, first discovered by R.S Sastri 1904<ol><li>literal meaning: science of statecraft</li><li>it contains 3 parts, 15 books and 180 chapters</li><li>1st part: king and council</li><li>2nd: civil and criminal law</li><li>3rd diplomacy and war</li></ol></li><li><b><i>Vishakhadatta&nbsp;Mudrarakshasa</i></b>, sanskrit written in gupta period, a play describes how kautilya helped CGM to overthrow Nandas<ol><li>it describes how CGM with kautilya overthrew nandas</li></ol></li><li>Hemachandra's Parishishta Parvan, tells about CGM relation with Jainism</li><li>Dandin's Dashakumaracharita</li><li>Banabhatta's kadambari</li><li>Megasthenes' Indica, greek ambassador of nicator</li><li><b><i>Others: jatkas, ceylonese chronicles, dipavamsa, mahavamsa</i></b>&nbsp;tells about Ashoka spreading&nbsp;buddhism</li><li>Inscription of <b>junagadh</b>, near Girnar, gujarat<ol><li>tells about extent of mauryan empire upto gujarat</li><li>name of CGM even after 400 years</li></ol></li><li>Edicts of Ashoka<ol><li>deciphered brahmi script at sanchi by james prinsep 1837</li><li>refer to ashoka as Devanampriya, piyadassi</li><li>puranic and buddhist texts refer to ashoka as Chakravartin</li><li>kharosthi: north west</li><li>pali, prakrit, , brahmi script for writing</li><li>13: kalinga</li><li>2: dhamma</li><li>7: promote dhamma</li></ol></li></ol></div><div><br></div><div><b><i>CGM 322-298 BC</i></b></div><div><ol><li>chandragupta maurya started mauryan empire by defeated&nbsp;<b>dhanananda</b></li><li>took over empire BC 324-299</li><li><b><i>seleucus nicator&nbsp;</i></b>came to fight with CGM</li><ol><li>cgm won, he sent 500 elephants to nicator</li><li>nicator gave his daughter to CGM</li><li><b>megasthenes&nbsp;</b>, ambassador of seleucus came to CGM court</li><li>he wrote Indica book, lived for 14 years in india</li></ol><li>Later CGM followed&nbsp;<b>jainism</b>, with bhadrabahu he went to south shravanabelagola</li><li>their CGM performed&nbsp;Sallekhana&nbsp;</li><li><b><i>Kautilya’s&nbsp;</i></b>Arthashastra</li><li><b><i>Vishakhadatta&nbsp;</i></b>Mudrarakshasa&nbsp;</li></ol></div><div><br></div><div><b><i>BINDUSARA 298-273 BC</i></b></div><div><ol><li>Amitraghata- slayer of enemies</li><li>Appointed&nbsp;&nbsp;<b><i>Ashoka as governor of Ujjain</i></b></li><li>conquered land between two seas, upto mysore</li><li>he also got Deimachus as ambassador from Syrian King Antiochus I</li><li>he also asked for wine, dried figs, a sophist, Antiochus sent all but sophist</li><li>supported ajivikas, a religious sect</li></ol></div><div><br></div><div><span style="font-size: 16.8px;"><b><i>ASHOKA 273-232 BC</i></b></span></div><div><ol><li>after CGM, bindusara</li><li>ashoka grandson of CGM</li><li>suppressed revolt a taxila when he was governor of ujjain</li><li>first 4 years spent to suppress his brothers</li><li>after kalinga war 261 BC, ashoka followed buddhism under monk <b>Nigrodha</b></li><ol><li>gradual conversion to buddhism</li><li>followed dharma vijaya,&nbsp;spread dharma through rock edicts</li><li>first became upasaka, disciple , 2 years later became Bikshu</li><li>visited bodh gaya and organised mission</li><li>ashoka appointed Dhamma-mahamattas to spread dhamma</li><li>under ashoka 3rd buddha council at pataliputra,&nbsp;<b><i>tissa&nbsp;</i></b>participated</li><li>his son mahendra spread dharma in ceylon</li></ol><li>Total 33 edicts,&nbsp;<b><i>14 major</i></b>, 2 kalinga edicts, 7 pillar edicts</li><ol><li>Language: brahmi, magadhi, prakrit script, kharosthi, kandahar&nbsp;region in greek and aramaic</li><li>Edict <b>1</b>: prohibit animal sacrifice</li><li><i>Edict </i><b style="">2</b><i>: dhamma explained ,</i>mention of&nbsp;<b>cholas</b>,&nbsp;<b>pandyas</b>, setup of hospitals in state</li><li>Edict <b style="font-style: italic;">3:</b>&nbsp;tour every 5 years to check if instructions are being carried out</li><li>Edict <b>5</b>: Dhamma-mahamattas to spread dhamma</li><li>Edict <b style="font-style: italic;">6</b>: ruler should be informed about his kingdom</li><li>Edict&nbsp;<b style="font-style: italic;">7:&nbsp;</b>religions should coexist and honoured, mention of <b>cholas</b>, pandyas</li><li>Edict <b>8</b>: royal pleasure tours</li><li>Edict <b>9</b>: criticizes useless ceremonies, lay stress on dhamma</li><li>Edict <b>10</b>:&nbsp; king desires no fame or glory</li><li>Edict <b>11</b>: policy of dhamma</li><li>Edict <b>13</b>: describes kalinga war 261 BC, digvijay replaced by Dhamma Vijay</li><li>Edict <b>14</b>: purpose of rock edicts</li></ol><li>Feroz shah tughlaq shifted pillars from meerut to delhi</li><li>Pillars Features<ol><li>monolithic, sandstone</li><li>without base 12-14 meter height</li><li>lotus, lions, bull, elephant</li></ol></li><li>Important Edicts<ol><li>Allahabad</li><ol><li>queen's edict</li><li>also mention of Samudragupta&nbsp;</li></ol><li>Girnar, inscription of Rudraman</li><ol><li>mention of sudarshan lake built by pushya gupta</li></ol><li>Kandahar inscription</li><ol><li>bilingual greek, aramaic</li></ol><li>Nighali Sagar, Nepal</li><ol><li>ashoka visited here</li></ol><li>Rummindei Nepal</li><ol><li>birthplace of buddha, ashoke visited lumbini</li></ol><li>Sannati inscription, karnataka</li><ol><li>14 major rock edicts</li></ol><li>Kalinga Edict</li><ol><li>mentions all men are my children</li></ol><li>Sohgaura Copper Plate</li><ol><li><b>relief</b> measures adopted during famine</li></ol><li>Shahbazgarhi and Mansehra in kharosthi language</li></ol></li><li>Barbara caves gifted to Ajivikas</li><li>stupas at sarnath, lumbini</li><li>highly polished stupa at sanchi</li><li>edicts written in Prakrit, kharosthi, brahmi script</li></ol></div><ol><li>Ashoka's Dhamma<ol><li>a broad concept containing moral values</li><li>service to parents, ahimsa, love of truth, humane treatment of servants etc</li><li>he did not equate dhamma with buddhist teachings</li><li>dhamma was general code and buddhism his personal belief</li></ol></li><li><b>Administration of Empire</b></li><ol><li>monarch rule, king assisted by council of ministers</li><li>purohita, mahamantri, senapati, yuvraha</li><li>all can be considered civil servants: Amatyas, a well organised administration</li><li>divided into 5 provinces</li><ol><li>north: taxila</li><li>west: ujjain, malwa</li><li>south: swarnagiri, kurnool AP</li><li>east: dosali, kalinga</li><li>main: magadha ruler by king, capital: Patliputra</li></ol><li>Mahamatras as <b><i>governors </i></b>for provinces</li><li><b><i>Rajukas</i></b>, officer similar to collector</li><li><b><i>Sthanika</i></b>, head of district</li><li><b><i>Gopa</i></b> head of 10-15 villages</li><li><b style="font-style: italic;">Gramini </b>head of Village, villages semi-autonomous</li><li>municipal administration under Nagarika&nbsp;</li></ol><li>City of Patliputra<ol><li>14 km length and 2.5km wide</li><li>64 gates and 570 watch towers</li></ol></li><li>Revenue system</li><ol><li><b>Samaharta</b>: chief of Revenue dept.</li><li>bali and bagha tax 1/6th of produce</li></ol><li>Army</li><ol><li>cash payments</li><li>megasthenes mention 6 boards of 5 members each to control 6 wings of military</li><li>navy, infantry, transport, supply</li></ol><li>Judicial and Police</li><ol><li>&nbsp;dharmasthiya courts, kantaka shodhana courts,&nbsp; civil and criminal courts</li><li>provincial and district courts under <b><i>Amatyas</i></b></li><li>police centres, jails, remission of unjust sentences&nbsp;</li></ol><li>Census<ol><li>regular census, including animals</li><li>by municipal officials, census was permanent administration</li></ol></li><li>Currency</li><ol><li>silver coins symbol <b>peacock</b></li><li>copper coins Mashakas, <b>Panna </b>in use</li></ol><li>Art and architecture<ol><li><b><i>Statues </i></b>of yakshas and yakshis<ol><li><b><i>Yakshas were deities </i></b>connected with water, fertility, trees, the forest and wilderness.</li><li>Yakshas&nbsp;were their female counterpart</li></ol></li><li><span style="font-size: 16.8px;"><b>Stupa of Sanchi</b></span></li><li><span style="font-size: 16.8px;"><b><i>Pillars</i></b>:<b> Sarnath Pillar by ashoka</b><i><ol><li>4 lions statue , adopted by indian govt. as state emblem</li></ol></i></span></li><li><span style="font-size: 16.8px;"><b>Caves</b><ol><li>caves of barabar hills new bodh gaya</li><li>interior is polished like mirror</li></ol></span></li><li><div>Silk was known referred to chinese silk</div></li><li><div>Craftsmen under royal workshops<ol><li>head pramukha and jetha or jyeshta</li></ol></div></li></ol></li><li>Later Mauryas<br><ol><li>ashoka died in 232 BC, empire division into two east and west</li><li>last ruler Brihadratha, killed by pushyamitra, started sunga dynasty</li></ol></li></ol><div><span style="font-size: 16.8px;">III.Match the following.&nbsp;</span></div><div><span style="font-size: 16.8px;">1.Dharma Mahamatras<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span></span><span style="font-size: 16.8px;">a) Village administration&nbsp;</span></div><div><span style="font-size: 16.8px;">2.Gopa<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span><span style="white-space: pre;">	</span><span style="white-space: pre;">	</span><span style="white-space: pre;">	<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span></span>b) Revenue administration&nbsp;</span></div><div><span style="font-size: 16.8px;">3.Nagarika<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span><span style="white-space: pre;">	</span><span style="white-space: pre;">	<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span></span>c) Spread of Dhamma&nbsp;</span></div><div><span style="font-size: 16.8px;">4.Samharta<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span><span style="white-space: pre;">	</span><span style="white-space: pre;">	<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span></span>d) City administration&nbsp;</span></div></div></div></div><div><br></div><div>Edicts of ashoka</div><div><img src="http://127.0.0.1:5500/images/edicts%20of%20ashoka.JPG"></div><div><br></div><div>Mauryan empire</div><div><img src="http://127.0.0.1:5500/images/mauryan%20empire.JPG"></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><div><div><div><div><div><br></div></div></div><div><br></div><div><br></div></div><div><br></div><div><br></div></div></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div></div>
    </div>`}


    ,{ title: "Chapter 9 Sungas, Satavahanas, Kushan ",content:`<input id="chapter" placeholder="Chapter" value="Chapter 9">
        <input class="subtitle" placeholder="Chapter Name" value="Sungas, Satavahanas, Kushan">
        <div class="editor" contenteditable="true">
            <div><b>THE SUNGAS: PUSHYAMITRA</b><ol><li>Brihadratha killed by&nbsp;<b>pushyamitra</b>, his general</li><li>capital: Patliputra</li><li>followed&nbsp;<b>brahmanism</b></li><li><b>fought with kalinga king kharavela</b></li><li>performed 2 ashvamedha yags</li><li>Kalidasa'&nbsp;<b>Malavikagnimitra</b><ol><li>narrates incident of challenging pushyamitra ashwamedha horse by yavanas</li></ol></li><li>importance fought against foreign invasions</li><li>promoted growth of vaishnavism and&nbsp;<b>sanskrit&nbsp;</b></li><li>described in hathigumpha inscription</li><li>Patanjali, noble grammarian wrote&nbsp;<b>Mahabhasya</b></li></ol><div><b><i>Agnimitra</i></b>, after son of pushyamitra&nbsp;</div><ol><li>Agnimitra</li><ol><li>hero of Kalidasa’s&nbsp;<b>Malavikagnimitra</b></li><li>yavana army challenged ashwamedha horse&nbsp;</li></ol></ol><div>Bhagabhadra<ol><li>mention in&nbsp;<b>Besnagar pillar&nbsp;</b>inscription of Heliodorus</li><li>in Vidisha, MP</li><li>worshipper of lord krishna</li></ol></div><div>Devabhuti</div><ol><li>last ruler&nbsp;<b><i>Devabhuti</i></b>, killed by his own minister Vasudeva(ouch)</li><li>Vasudeva formed Kanva Dynasty</li></ol><div><br></div><div><b>The Kanvas</b><ol><li>short 45 year rule</li><li>founded by&nbsp;<b>Vasudeva</b></li><li>last ruler Susarman killed by Simuka</li><li>simuka founded Satavahana dynasty in south</li></ol><div><b>THE SATAVAHANAS IN SOUTH:</b>&nbsp;<span style="-webkit-text-fill-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"><b>SIMUKA</b></span></div><ol><li>kushanas in north for 300 and Satavahanas in south for 450 years 1st to 3rd Century</li><li>independent rule in south</li><li>Source<ol><li>puranas and inscriptions</li><li><b>nasik&nbsp;</b>and&nbsp;<b>nanaghat&nbsp;</b>inscription tells about&nbsp;<b>Gautamiputra&nbsp;</b>Satakarni</li></ol></li><li>Coins: symbol horse, ships</li><li>Ruler: Simuka, next Krishna</li><li><b><i>Gautamiputra Satakarni</i></b>&nbsp;<ol><li>greatest ruler ruled for 24 years</li><li>destroyer of yavans, pahlavas</li><li>defeated ruler of Nahapana and reissued coins in his own insignia</li><li>conquered western malwa and berar</li><li>defeated Nagapana, ruler of malwa</li><li>described in nasik inscription</li><li>patronized brahmanism and also gave donations to buddhists</li><li>also performed ashvamedha sacrifice</li></ol></li><li><b><i>Hala</i></b></li><ol><li>another great ruler for 5 years</li><li>famous book&nbsp;<b><i>Gaha</i></b>&nbsp;<b><i>Sattasai</i></b>, 700 love poems in&nbsp;<b><i>prakrit&nbsp;</i></b>literature</li></ol><li><b>Vasista Putra Pulumavi</b></li><ol><li>son of Gautamiputra, extended power upto mouth of krishna</li><li>issue coins symbol ship</li><li>great naval power and trade</li></ol><li>Last ruler: Yajna Sri Satakarni, coins with ship motifs</li><li><b>Economy</b></li><ol><li>progress in trade and industry</li><li>merchants organised guilds</li><li>currency: silver coins- Karshapanas&nbsp;</li><li>revenue collection in both: cash and kind</li><li>Satavahanas first one to give tax free lands to brahmans and buddhists</li><li>port:&nbsp;<b>kalyani&nbsp;</b>in west deccan, gandhakasala and ganjam on east coast</li><li>they used burnt bricks</li><li>underground drainage system</li></ol><li><b>Cultural contribution</b><ol><li>patronized&nbsp;<b>buddhism&nbsp;</b>and&nbsp;<b>brahmanism</b></li><li>performed vedic rituals, sacrifices</li><li>due to vedic influence, varna system</li><li>built chaityas(prayer halls) and viharas(stayed during rainy season)</li><li>official language Prakrit, script used Brahmi</li><li>patronized prakrit language, hala's sattasai excellent example</li><li><b><i>naneghat inscription</i></b>, western ghats, maharashtra, mentions about tax exemptions given to land granted to buddhist monks.</li></ol></li></ol><div><br></div><div><b>Post mauryan period</b><ol><li>after indo-greek relation increased, tribes Sakas(scythians), parthians(pahlavis) and Kushans(yueh chi tribe) came</li><li>period is not clear and history is blur here</li><li>north: sungas and kanvas</li><li><b>south: satavahana</b></li><li>north-west: sakas, kushans</li></ol></div><div><br></div><div><b>THE SHAKAS OR SCYTHIANS</b><ol><li>sakas pushed by parthian rulers from iran to north west india</li><li>First Saka Ruler: <b>MAUES</b>: founder of saka rule in india 1st BC</li><li>in north west and western part, gandhara region</li><li>his son <b>Azes</b> founder of <b>Vikram Era</b>, extended sakas rule</li><li>sakas adopted hindu religion</li><ol><li>names, coins hindu gods</li></ol><li>Sakas appointed Kshatrapas as governor of provinces<ol><li>famous Kshatrapas, <b>Rudraman</b></li><li>mention in junagadh inscription, gujarat</li></ol></li><li>Overthrown by parthians</li></ol></div><div><br></div><div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><b><i>KUSHAN EMPIRE</i></b></div><div><ol><li>branch of yueh-chi tribes means moon tribe, originally from central Asia</li><li>they displaces sakas from bactria region(central asia )</li><li>then moved to kabul valley, gandhara region</li><li>First ruler, founder: Kujula&nbsp;<b>Kadphises</b>&nbsp;I</li><li>Later, Wima&nbsp;<b>Kadphises</b>&nbsp;II, issued coin with title&nbsp;<b><i>Lord of Whole World</i></b></li><li>they extended territory to gandhara, punjab, upto ganga-yamuna doab till mathura in UP</li><li>devotee of Shiva</li></ol></div><div><b><i>KANISHAA&nbsp;</i></b>AD 78-101&nbsp;<b>SAKA ERA</b>, also called Ashoka II<ol><li>saka era, still used by govt. for calendar</li><li>Aftermost powerful king of kushans</li><li>rock of Hunza,Karakoram Highway, mentions about first two Kadphises and Kanishka refer as Kusan Devaputra</li><li>Rabatak inscription provides information about Kanishka</li><li>also karakoram highway take up by buddhist monks to go to china</li><li>at his time empire included afghanistan, gandhara, sind, punjab</li><li>he conquered magadh, patliputra, bodh gaya, also invaded kashmir</li><li>fought with chinese twice</li><ol><li>first :lost to pancho</li><li>second: won and annexed&nbsp;<b>kashgar</b>, khotan, central asia</li></ol><li>2 capitals<ol><li>purushapura (peshawar)</li><li>Mathura</li></ol></li><li>patronized buddha, mahayana buddhism in fashion</li><li>Religious tolerant, motifs of both shiva and buddha</li><li>coins including buddha, greek and hindu gods</li><li>4th council kashmir : mahayana came in vague</li><ol><li>president:&nbsp;<b><i>Vasumitra</i></b></li><li>vasubandhu, nagarjuna,</li><li>Ashvaghosha wrote buddhacharita and Sariputra Prakarana&nbsp;&nbsp;</li><li>held at kundalavana monastery near srinagar</li><li>split into hinayana or mahayana</li><li>commentary on tripitakas</li><li><b>ashwaghosh favoured mahayana wrote buddhacharita</b></li><li>mahayana spread to tibet and china</li></ol><li><b style="font-style: italic;">Vasumitra :&nbsp;</b>Mahavibhasa, Buddhist philosophy text</li><li><b>Ashvaghosha</b>: Buddhacarita</li><li><b><i>Charaka</i></b>, famous physician belonged to kanishka empire</li><li><b>Nagarjuna</b>: indian einstein</li><li><b>Gandhara&nbsp;</b>art combined indo-greek,roman style new statues of buddha and bodhisattvas</li><li>greek influence on gandhara art</li><li>ajanta caves, kanheri caves, buddhist, chaityas and viharas were established</li></ol></div><div>VASUDEVA II<ol><li>last kushan ruler</li></ol></div><div><br></div><div><b>Gandhara art</b><ol><li>home of art around peshawar in northwestern india</li><li>around 1st and 2nd century</li><li>origin: indo-greek, blend of indian and graeco-roman elements</li><li>Patron: sakas, kushans, Kanishka</li><li>sculptures of buddha in various sizes, shapes, postures</li><li>depicts birth, renunciation, preaching</li><li>Features</li><ol><li>moulding human body in realistic manner</li><li>minute attention to physical features, muscles, moustache, curly hair</li><li>thick drapery, large and bold fold lines</li><li>rich carving, elaborate ornamentation, symbolic expressions</li><li>main theme : Mahayanism</li></ol><li><div>Buddha statue cut out of rock at bahaman valley, afghanistan belongs to Gandhara School of art</div><div>gandhar is influenced by greek</div></li></ol><div><b>Mathura School of art</b><ol><li>developed at UP</li><li>in 1st century</li><li>main feature: spiritual feelings which were absent in gandhara art</li><li>images of shiva, vishnu, parvati, laxmi</li><li>female figures yakshini and apsaras</li><li>headless<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>statue of<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>Kanishka</li></ol><div><br></div></div></div></div></div></div>
        </div>`}

    ,{ title: "Chapter 10 Guptas, Harsh ",content:`<input id="chapter" placeholder="Chapter" value="Chapter 10">
    <input class="subtitle" placeholder="Chapter Name" value="Guptas, Harsh">
    <div class="editor" contenteditable="true">
        <div><br></div><div><div><b style="font-style: italic;">THE GUPTA EMPIRE</b></div><div>Period: 300-700 AD</div><div>Founder: Sri Gupta</div><div>Capital: Patliputra</div><div>Symbol: Garuda<br><div><span style="-webkit-text-fill-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"><b><br></b></span></div><div><span style="font-size: 16.8px; -webkit-text-fill-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"><b>SOURCES</b></span></div><div><ol><li>Puranas</li><li><b>Vishakhadatta</b>: Devichandraguptam and Mudrarakshasa&nbsp;</li><li>Fahien&nbsp;during&nbsp;Chandragupta II</li><li><b>Mehrauli&nbsp;</b>Pillar erected by Chandra Gupta contains inscription of chandra gupta 1</li><li><b>Allahabad&nbsp;</b>Pillar of ashoka bores SamudraGupta's name<ol><li>used <b>Nagari</b> script, classical sanskrit</li><li>describes Samudragupta military and other works</li><li>lines composed by Harisena</li></ol></li><li>Coins: containing figures and legends</li><li>coins tell about vedic rituals followed in this period</li></ol><div><br></div></div><div><div><span style="font-size: 16.8px;"><b>CHANDRAGUPTA&nbsp;I 320-330 AD</b></span></div></div><ol><li><b style="font-style: italic;">Gupta era </b>beings</li><li>son of Ghatotkacha</li><li>Title: Maharajadhiraj</li><li>married kumar devi, princes of licchavis&nbsp;</li><li>Mehrauli pillar mentions his extensive conquests</li></ol><div><br></div><div><div><span style="font-size: 16.8px;"><b><br></b></span></div><div><span style="font-size: 16.8px;"><b>SAMUDRAGUPTA 330-380 AD</b></span></div><div><span style="font-size: 16.8px;">Napoleon, Kaviraj with Veena, 9 gems</span></div></div><div><ol><li>Allahabad inscription erected by Ashoka, Harisena composed lines on this pillar<ol><li><b>Three stage military conquest</b></li><li>First Against north<ol><li>gained control over gangetic plains by defeating achyuta</li></ol></li><li>Second Dakshinapatha in south<ol><li>defeated 12 rulers, did not annex but insisted them to acknowledge his <b>suzerainty</b></li></ol></li><li>Third Again north<ol><li>defeated remaining rulers, 9 kings in total</li></ol></li></ol></li><li>Performed&nbsp;<b>asvamedha sacrifices</b></li><li>issued gold and silver coins with legend asvamedha, horses, also of him with veena</li><li>great promotion of sanskrit</li><li>Follower of Vaishnavism</li><li><b>NINE</b> gems in his court<ol><li>Kalidasa:&nbsp;Sakunthalam, Malavikagnimitram and&nbsp;Vikramorvasiyam</li><li>Amarasimha: wrote amarakosa</li><li>Visakhadatta&nbsp;: Mudrarakshasa&nbsp;and Devichandraguptam</li><li>Dhanvantri: great physician, father of ayurveda</li><li>Harisena: composed allahabad pillar</li><li>Kahapanaka</li><li>Sanku</li><li>Varahamihira: Panch Sidhanta, Brihat Samhita</li><li>Vararuchi</li><li>Vetala Bhatta</li></ol></li><li><b><i>Extent of Samudragupta</i></b></li><ol><li>upper gangetic valley</li><li>central india, south west part of bengal</li><li>saka and kushans were in influenced by him</li></ol><li><b>Estimate of Samudragupta</b><ol><li>remarkable military achievements will remain in annals of history</li><li>Allahabad pillar inscription speaks of his polished intellect, poetic skill and proficiency in music</li><li>Title: Kaviraja, composing verses</li><li>image of him with <b>veena</b>, issued on coins</li><li><b>horse</b> sacrifice ritual</li><li>tolerant towards other religions</li><li>patronized buddhism , and followed vaishnavism, promoted sanskrit&nbsp;</li></ol></li></ol></div><div><span style="-webkit-text-fill-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"><b><br></b></span></div><div><span style="-webkit-text-fill-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"><b><br></b></span></div><div><span style="-webkit-text-fill-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"><b><br></b></span></div><div><span style="font-size: 16.8px; -webkit-text-fill-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"><b>CHANDRAGUPTA II( VIKRAMADITYA )</b></span></div><div><ol><li>Son of Samudragupta</li><li>Conquest of western India<ol><li>war against saka satraps, he defeated them</li><li>assumed Title:&nbsp;<b><i>Sakari</i></b>, destroyer of sakas, also&nbsp;<b><i>Vikramaditya</i></b></li><li>annexed western malwa and kathiawar</li><li><b>Horse</b> Sacrifices</li><li>Ujjain emerged as important and alternative capital</li><li>trade with Roman empire, gold coins of romans</li><li>he also crossed sindh and captured Bacteria</li><li>kushans ruling in this region were subdued by him</li><li>gupta empire limits<ol><li>north: hindu kush mts. upto Bactria</li><li>west : malwa, gujarat, kathiawar</li><li>east: bengal</li><li>south: till narmada</li></ol></li></ol></li><li><b>Fahien came</b></li><ol><li>out of 9 years in india, he spent 6 years in gupta empire</li><li>came through route of northwest, khotan, gandhara, punjab</li><li>and further went towards ceylon and java through sea route</li><li>purpose: see land of buddha, collect manuscripts, not interested in political affairs of state</li><li>main aim buddhism</li><li>stayed at patliputra 3 years studying sanskrit, and copied buddhist texts</li><li>his accounts provide information about gupta empire</li><li>buddhism flourished in north west but neglected in gangetic valley, their brahmanism was popular</li></ol><li>Estimate of Chandragupta II</li><ol><li>power under it peak</li><li>kalidas lived</li><li>first one to issue <b>silver </b>coins</li><li>due to promotion of culture, age is called golden age</li><li>9 gems in his court</li><li>Dhanvantri: great physician</li></ol></ol></div><ol><li><b>Kumaragupta</b></li><ol><li>son of chandragupta II</li><li>issued coins, performed sacrifices horses</li><li>foundation of&nbsp;<b>Nalanda&nbsp;</b>University</li><li>after Kumaragupta, successors defeated by Huns invasion</li></ol><li>Skanda Gupta death, decline of gupta empire</li><li>Vishnu Gupta, last of Guptas</li></ol><div><span style="-webkit-text-fill-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);"><b><br></b></span></div><ol><li><b>Administration</b><ol><li style="font-style: italic;">king assumed titles <b>Maharajadhiraj</b>, Samrat</li><li style="font-style: italic;">Ministers and officials<ol><li>Kumar Amatya, Adhikarana high ranking officer</li><li>assisted by council , chief minister, senapati</li><li>Amatya, equal to royal princes</li><li>sandhi vigrahika and maha sandhi vigraha minister of peace and war</li></ol></li><li style="font-style: italic;">provincial administration under Kumara Matyas, ayuktas</li><ol style="font-style: italic;"><li>Province: named <b>Bhuktis </b>under Uparikas, governors</li><li>bhuktis into vaishyas, districts under Vishyapatis</li><li>City under Nagara Srishtis</li><li>Villages under Gramikas</li></ol><li><i>Economic&nbsp;</i><ol><li style="font-style: italic;">akshapataladhikrita was the keeper of royal records</li><li style="font-style: italic;">famous for pepper and cardamom</li><li><i>Division of Land</i></li><ol><li style="font-style: italic;"><b>Kshetra </b>Cultivable land&nbsp;</li><li style="font-style: italic;"><b>Khila </b>Waste land&nbsp;</li><li style="font-style: italic;"><b>Aprahata </b>Jungle or waste land&nbsp;</li><li style="font-style: italic;"><b>Vasti</b> Habitable land&nbsp;</li><li><b>Gapata&nbsp;</b><i>Saraha Pastoral land</i></li></ol><li><i>Grants<ol><li>Agrahara grants: to brahmins, tax free</li><li>dev agrahara grants: for temple</li></ol></i></li></ol></li><li style="font-style: italic;">administration mild and benevolent, no restriction on movement</li><li style="font-style: italic;">spy system known as Dutakas</li><li style="font-style: italic;">common punishment, roads were safe, low crime rate</li></ol></li><li>Irrigation<ol><li>formation of dykes,&nbsp;</li><li>baradhya: protection from floods</li><li>khara: for irrigation</li><li>jalani graham, drains were created</li><li>famous lake, <b>sudarsana lake</b> at girnar hills, gujarat</li></ol></li><li>Peasantry<ol><li>undermined, reduced to serfs , labours</li><li>lease-holding system, required to pay taxes</li><li>Taxes</li><ol><li><b>bhaga</b>: normal tax 1/6th</li><li>bhoga: periodic supple of foods&nbsp;</li><li>kara: on villagers</li><li>bali: voluntary tax to king</li><li>upari kara: extra tax</li><li><b>hiranya</b>, tax on gold coins</li><li>sulka, royal share</li></ol></ol></li><li><b>Social Life</b><ol><li><b>rigid </b>caste system</li><li><b>untouchability </b>arises, chandals segregated from society</li><li>women prohibited from studying religious texts</li><li>swayamvara practice stopped and child marriage prevailed</li><li>brahmanism rises, vaishnavism, shaivism, guptas followed vaishnavism</li><li>ashwamedha sacrifices, idol worship</li><li>decline of buddhism due to brahmanism</li><li>jain council at valabhi held, svetambaras was written</li></ol></li><li><b>Art and culture</b></li><ol><li>growth in science, art, literature</li><li>nagara and dravidian styles evolved, but lost due to Huns invasion</li><li>temple at deogarh, jhansi spicment of gupta empire</li><li>no influence of gandhara style</li><li>buddha statue unearthed from sarnath is of gupta period</li><li>Mehrauli&nbsp;Pillar in delhi, is of gupta period</li><li>Bagh caves, gwalior,&nbsp;</li><li>painting of Ajanta, jataka stories</li><li>paintings of Sigiriya, Sri Lanka</li><li>gold coins, Samudragupta issued 8 types of gold coins, symbols, horse, kings&nbsp;</li></ol><li>Rock cut and temples</li><ol><li>found at ajanta and ellora</li><li>bagh MP</li><li>udayagiri caves orissa</li><li><b>features</b></li><li>flat-roofed square, second storey, rectangular temple, circular temple</li></ol><li>Statues</li><ol><li>copper image of buddha 18 feet nalanda bihar</li><li>sultanganj, bihar 7 feet</li></ol><li>Painting</li><ol><li>mural paintings found at ajanta, bagh, badami</li><li>mural paintings of ajanta are not frescoes</li><li>pottery red ware</li></ol><li><b>Literature</b><ol><li>sanskrit language official, nagari script evolved form brahmi script</li><li><b>panini </b>wrote Ashtadhyayi</li><li>amarakosa by amarasimha, a sanskrit thesaurus</li><li>arya deva and arya asanga important work of gupta period related to&nbsp;<b>buddhism</b>.</li><li>nagari script is used on Mehrauli&nbsp;Pillar</li><li>Kalidas, sanskrit drama<ol><li><b>Shakuntala</b>,&nbsp;</li><li>Meghaduta</li><li>Malavikagnimitra</li><li>Vikramorvasiya.&nbsp;</li><li>Raghuvamsa&nbsp;</li><li>Kumarasambhava</li><li>Ritusamhara .</li></ol></li><li><b><i>Vishakhadatta&nbsp;</i></b>Mudrarakshasa, Devichandraguptam, sanskrit dramas</li><li>Sudraka wrote&nbsp;Mrichchhakatika</li><li>Dandin wrote Kavyadarsa and Dasakumaracharita&nbsp;</li><li>The Panchatantra by Vishnu Sharma during the Gupta period</li><li><b>Epic compiled in this age</b></li></ol></li><ol><li>ramayanas</li><li>mahabharata</li><li><span style="font-size: 16.8px;">18 puranas</span></li><li>Panchathanthiram&nbsp;</li></ol><li><b>Science</b><ol><li>aryabhata wrote book aryabhatiya 499 AD, maths and astronomy</li><li>Brahmagupta: invention of zero, earth revolves around its own axis</li><li>Surya Siddhanta, by aryabhatiya, cause of eclipse</li><li>first to declare earth is round and rotates on its own axis</li><li>Varahamihira composed Pancha Siddhantika, the five astronomical systems</li><li>he also wrote brihat samhita, astronomy</li><li>Vagbhata, great medical person wrote Ashtanga Samgraha (Summary of the eight branches of medicine).</li><li><b><i>Charaka and Sushruta before gupta age</i></b></li></ol></li><li>Kalidas, aryabhata</li><li>varahamihira, physicians</li><li>ajanta caves to this age</li><li>Nalanda University founded by kumaragupta<ol><li>mahayana buddhist monastery in magadha, bihar</li><li>UNESCO world heritage site</li><li>flourished under gupta empire</li><li>destroyed by Mamluk Dynasty of delhi sultanate</li></ol></li><li>caste system was prevalent, sacrifices</li></ol><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><b style="font-style: italic;">HARSHA DYNASTY&nbsp;</b></div><div>Founder: Pushyabhuti</div><div><ol><li>after decline of gupta empire, political disorder and disunity in north india</li><li>in beginning of 7th century Harshavardhan succeeded in established kingdom</li><li>Sources<ol><li>Harshacharita by Bana, court poet</li><li>Harsha wrote, Ratnavali, nagananda, priyadarshika</li><li>Hiuen Tsang Si YU Ki</li><li>Plates of Madhuban</li><li>Sonipat inscription</li><li><b>Banskhera</b> inscriptions UP, contains signature of Harsha</li></ol></li><li>Founder</li><ol><li><b>Pushyabhuti</b>, feudatories of Guptas, called themselves Vardhanas</li><li>after Huns invasion, gupta empire decline and they assumed independence</li><li>first important king prabhakara vardhana, capital Thaneswar</li><li>next his elder son Rajyavardhana came to throne, he was murdered</li><li>next Harsha his brother became king of Thaneswar</li></ol><li>Harshvardhan&nbsp;606 to 647 AD<ol><li>shift capital Thaneswar to <b>Kannauj</b></li><li>important, fought against western Chalukyas ruler Pulakesin II</li><li>harsha saved his sister in vindhya ranges, killed Deva Gupta</li><li>harsha wanted to extend territory south of narmada, but failed</li><li><b>Aihole </b>inscription of Pulakesin II and Hiuen Tsang confirms <b>defeat </b>of Harsha</li><li>harsha gained control over kashmir and nepal</li><li>last campaign against kalinga orissa and it was success</li><li>Buddhism</li><ol><li>devout of shiva but later adopted Hinayana Buddhist</li><li>but Hiuen Tsang converted him into mahayana</li><li>he erected thousands of stupas</li><li>also conducted once in five year assembly</li></ol><li>Kannauj Assembly for 23 days, arson,&nbsp;</li><ol><li>assembly to honour Hiuen-tsang, a mahayana promoter</li><li>attended by 20 kings, 1000 scholars from Nalanda University</li><li>Hiuen-tsang, explained importance of mahayana</li><li>but violence broke out, act of arson, also attempt on life of Harsha</li><li>at the end he distributed wealth</li></ol><li>Allahabad Conference&nbsp;</li><ol><li>held at prayag, one of conference convened by harsha once in 5 years</li><li>harsha gave way wealth&nbsp;</li></ol><li>Harsha's Administration</li><ol><li>same as on line of gupta</li><li>taxation was light and forced labour</li><li>tax normal 1/6th</li><li>cruel punishments of Mauryan continued but harsha condemned barbarou trials</li><li>army into 4 division<ol><li>foot, horse, charito, elephant</li><li>more army than Mauryans&nbsp;</li></ol></li><li>Archive called as&nbsp;<b>Nilopitu</b></li></ol><li><b><i>Society and Economy</i></b></li><ol><li>varna system 4 castes<ol><li>brahmins</li><li>kshatriyas: ruling class</li><li>vysya: traders</li><li>sudras: lower class, agriculture</li></ol></li><li>swayamvara declined, child marriage, no widow marriage, sati</li><li>dowry became common</li><li>cremation, water burial, exposure in woods</li><li>trade declined, led to self-sufficient villages</li><li>compared to gupta period, decline in economy</li></ol><li>Cultural Progress<ol><li>art followed of gupta period</li><li>Hiuen-tsang described monasteries built by harsha at Nalanda</li><li>harsha patronized Nalanda, it became international reputed University</li><li>copper statue of buddha height 8 feet</li><li>Brick temple of Lakshmana, Sirpur, Chhattisgarh</li><li>harsha great patron of learning wrote Ratnavali, priyadarshika, nagananda</li><li>bana wrote Harshacharita, kadambari</li><li>another famous person in court, Bhartrihari was poet, philosopher, grammarian</li></ol></li></ol></li></ol><div><br></div></div></div><div>Nalanda University Kumaragupta<ol><li>Other Hinayana University of Valabhi</li><li>Mahanya University of Nalanda</li><li>Hiuen-tsang gave valuable account of University, he himself was student of University</li><li>nalanda means: giver of knowledge founded by Kumaragupta, patronized by Harsha</li><li>Dharmapala, native of kanchipuram , became head of University</li><li>it was residential, free education including boarding, lodging</li><li>maintained revenue derived from 100-200 villages</li><li>being a mahayana University, other religious subjects like vedas, hinayana, yoga were taught</li><li>admission via entrance exam, medium sanskrit</li></ol></div><div><br></div><div>THE PALAS OF BENGAL</div><div>Area: Eastern gangetic plains</div><div>Founder: Gopala&nbsp;</div><div>Religion: Rise of buddhism</div><div>Sanskrit, Prakrit, Pali Language</div><div><br></div><div>RULERS<ol><li>Dharampala son of Gopala</li><ol><li>great patron of Buddhism</li><li>founded: <b>Vikramshila </b>University, Bhagalpur district Bihar</li></ol><li>Devpala son of Dharmapala</li><ol><li>defeated Amoghavarsha, Rashtrakuta ruler</li><li>revival of Nalanda&nbsp;University</li></ol><li>later Vigramapala abdicated throne<ol><li>Rashtrakutas took advantage</li><li>Palas ruler over</li></ol></li></ol></div><div>RELIGION<ol><li>mahayana buddhism rises</li><li>Haribhadra, spiritual preceptor of Dharmapala</li></ol></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div>Match the following&nbsp;</div><div>1. Fourth Buddhist Council -- Kashmir&nbsp;</div><div>2. Samudra Gupta's period -- AD 335- AD 375&nbsp;</div><div>3. Kanishka's period -- AD 78-AD 101&nbsp;</div><div>4. Pannar -- Priyadarshika</div><div>5. Harsha --&nbsp; Harshacharita&nbsp;</div><div>6. Kushan -- Yueh-Chi tribe&nbsp;</div><div>7. Ashoka ll --&nbsp; Kanishka&nbsp;</div><div>8. Nalanda University --Kumaragupta</div><div>9. Kadphises -- Established Kushan Empire&nbsp;</div><div><br></div><div>&nbsp;</div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div></div>
    </div>`}

    ,{ title: "Chapter 11 Pallavas, Chalukyas, Rashtrakutas ",content:`<input id="chapter" placeholder="Chapter" value="Chapter 11">
    <input class="subtitle" placeholder="Chapter Name" value="Pallavas, Chalukyas, Rashtrakutas">
    <div class="editor" contenteditable="true">
        <div><div><br></div><div><div><div><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;"><i style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; font-size: 30.8px;">PALLAVAS 250-800 AD</i></b></div><div><br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"></div><div><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">INTRO:ORIGIN OF PALLAVAS!</b><ol><li>Capital:&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">KANCHIPURAM</b></li><li>Region:&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">TONDAIMANDALAM</b></li><li>3 stage rule from 250-800 AD, almost 550 years</li><li>Pallavas ruled till arrival of Imperial Cholas, last Ruler <b>APARAJITA </b>defeated by Aditya, Cholas</li><li>accepted view by scholars, pallavas were natives of<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">TONDAIMANDALAM</b></li><li>when Satavahanas ruled over Tondaimandalam, pallavas were their feudatories</li><li>after fall of Satavahanas, pallavas inscription in Prakrit and later in Sanskrit and Tamil</li><li>they patronized&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">BRAHMANISM(SHAVISM MOSTLY)</b></li></ol><div><div><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">SOURCES: HOW DO WE KNOW ABOUT PALLAVAS?</b><br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"><ol><li><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">COPPER PLATES&nbsp;</b>inscriptions, issued by Chalukyas in kannada, telugu, tamil, sanskrit</li><li><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">AIHOLE&nbsp;</b>inscription of&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">PULAKESIN II&nbsp;</b>composed by&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">RAVIKIRTI&nbsp;</b>in&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">SANSKRIT</b>, Chalukyas</li><li>Book:&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">KAVIRAJAMARGA</b>&nbsp;in kannada by&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">AMOGHAVARSHA I</b>&nbsp;of Rashtrakutas</li><li>Pampa-bharata by Pampa in kannada</li><li>Mahabharatam by Nannaya</li><li>Bhakti movement during pallavas,&nbsp;</li><li>Vaishnavite:&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">AZHWARS&nbsp;</b>compiled&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">NALAYIRA</b>&nbsp;Divya Prabhandam</li><li>Shavist:&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">NANYANMAR</b>&nbsp;composed&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">DEVARAM</b></li><li><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">MAHENDRAVARMAN I</b>&nbsp;wrote&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">MATTAVILASA PRAHASANA&nbsp;</b></li><li>Kuram copper plates of Parameswara Varman</li><li>Velipalayam copper plates by Nandivarman II</li><li>Buddhist sources, Dipavamsa, mahavamsa in Pali</li><li>accounts of&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">HIUEN-TSANG</b>, came during NARASIMHAVARMAN&nbsp;II</li></ol></div><div><br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"></div><div><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">POLITICAL HISTORY OF PALLAVAS</b><ol><li>Three stage rule</li><li><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">FIRST</b>: 250-350 AD, used prakrit, language used by common people</li><li><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">SECOND</b>; 350-550 AD, used Sanskrit, may be due to rise of Brahmanism</li><ol><li>in this period, ruler&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">VISHNU GOPA DEFEATED BY SAMUDRAGUPTA</b>&nbsp;during South expedition</li></ol><li><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">THIRD</b>: 575 AD till 9th century</li><ol><li>use of both sanskrit and tamil</li><li><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">SIMHAVISHNU</b>, first ruler of line, destroyed Kalabhras and established rule over Tondaimandalam</li><li>he also defeated cholas and capture upto kaveri river</li></ol><li>Main rulers:&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">MAHENDRAVARMAN I, NARASIMHAVARMAN I AND NARASIMHAVARMAN II&nbsp;</b>g</li></ol><div><br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"></div><div><br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"></div><div><table border="0" width="" style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;width: 80%;border-collapse: collapse;margin: auto;"><colgroup style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"><col width="296" style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; width: 222pt;"><col width="290" span="2" style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; width: 217pt;"></colgroup><tbody style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"><tr height="19" style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; height: 14.4pt;"><td height="19" class="xl65" width="296" style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; border: 1px solid white; height: 14.4pt; width: 222pt;"><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">MAHENDRAVARMAN I 600-630 AD</b></td><td class="xl65" width="290" style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; border-top: 1px solid white; border-right: 1px solid white; border-bottom: 1px solid white; border-left: none; border-image: initial; width: 217pt;"><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">NARASIMHAVARMAN I 630-668 AD</b></td><td class="xl65" width="290" style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; border-top: 1px solid white; border-right: 1px solid white; border-bottom: 1px solid white; border-left: none; border-image: initial; width: 217pt;">NARASIMHAVARMAN II or <b>RAJASIMHA </b>695-722 AD</td></tr><tr height="546" style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; height: 409.6pt;"><td height="546" class="xl68" width="296" style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; border-top: none; border-right: 1px solid white; border-bottom: 1px solid white; border-left: 1px solid white; border-image: initial; height: 409.6pt; width: 222pt;">Pallava and Chalukya&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">CONFLICT BEGAN</b><br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"><br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">Pulakesin II captured Northern part of their kingdom<br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"><br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">although Mahendravarman I won but failed to recover the loss<br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"><br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">FOLLOWED JAIN</b>&nbsp;but&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">LATER SAIVISM</b>, after influence of Saiva saint Thriunavukkarasar alias&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">APPAR</b><br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">built Shiva temple at tiruvadi<br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"><br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">Title:&nbsp;<font class="font5" style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">CHATTAKARI</b></font><font class="font0" style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">&nbsp;(builder of temples)<br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">Chitrakarapuli &gt; also talent of painting and music<br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">Vichitrachita<br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">Mattavilasa<br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">Music inscription at Kudumianmalai about him, knowledge of music"<br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"><br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">Great builder of caves, started first stage of temple building: only using rock cut technology<br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">he introduced rock cut temples<br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"><br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">"<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">MANDAGAPATTU</b>&nbsp;inscription refers to him as Vivhitrachitta<br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">constructed temples of brahma, vishnu, shiva without using rocks, timber, metal and mortar"<br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"><br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">he wrote book:&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">MATTAVILASA PRAHASANA</b>, a satire play written in Sanskrit&nbsp;</font></td><td class="xl67" width="290" style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; border-top: none; border-right: 1px solid white; border-bottom: 1px solid white; border-left: none; border-image: initial; width: 217pt;">also known as&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">MAMALLA</b>, means great Wrestler<br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">he&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">FOUNDED MAMALLAPURAM</b><br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"><br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">Avenge death of his father at hands of Chalukyas ruler Pulakesin II<br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"><br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">"<b>Battle of&nbsp;<font class="font5" style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">Manimangalam</font></b><font class="font0" style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">near kanchi, he won<br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">mentioned in&nbsp;</font><font class="font5" style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">Kurram Copper</font><font class="font0" style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">&nbsp;plates"<br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"><br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">His general <b>Paranjothi</b> destroyed Chalukya Army&gt;Captured Vatapi<br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">pallav army completely destroyed Chalukyan army and captured city Vatapi<br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"><br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">Title :&nbsp;</font><font class="font5" style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"><b>Vatapikonda</b></font><font class="font0" style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"><br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">he also marched towards sri lanka, and restored throne to Manavarma<br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"><br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"></font><font class="font5" style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"><b>Hiuen-tsang</b></font><font class="font0" style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">&nbsp;came, he gave vivid description of pallav city capital kanchipuram<br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">beautiful city, 6 miles circumference<br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">100 monasteries, 10000 monks&nbsp;<br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">great learning centre<br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">great monolithic rathas were erected during his reign<br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"></font></td><td class="xl67" width="290" style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; border-top: none; border-right: 1px solid white; border-bottom: 1px solid white; border-left: none; border-image: initial; width: 217pt;">his period is peaceful and more art and architecture development<br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"><br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">built<br><b><font class="font5" style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">Shore temple</font><font class="font0" style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">&nbsp;at&nbsp;</font><font class="font5" style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">Mamallapuram<br></font><font class="font5" style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">Kailasanatha temple kanchipuram</font></b><font class="font0" style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"><br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"><br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"></font><font class="font5" style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">DANDIN</b></font><font class="font0" style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">, Sanskrit scholar in his court, wrote&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">DASHAKUMARACHARITA&nbsp;</b><br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">Sent embassies to china and maritime trade flourshed<br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">Rajasimha assumed title: Sankarabhakta, Agamapriya<br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">after that pallavas rule lasted till 9 Century<br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">APARAJITA</b>: Last ruler defeated by Chola king Aditya I<br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">End of pallava rulers</font></td></tr></tbody></table></div><div><br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"></div><div><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase; font-size: 21.8px;">MAHENDRAVARMAN I 600-630 AD</b><ol><li>long drawn Pallava and Chalukya conflict began in this period</li><li>although Mahendravarman I won but failed to recover the loss</li><li>early he followed Jain but later&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">SAIVISM</b>, after influence of Saiva saint</li><li>he also&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">BUILT SHIVA TEMPLE AT TIRUVADI</b></li><li>assumed title:&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;"><i style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">CHATTAKARI(BUILDER OF TEMPLES)</i></b>, also talent of painting and music</li><li>great builder of caves, temple only using&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;"><i style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">ROCK CUT</i></b>&nbsp;technology</li><li>he&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">INTRODUCED ROCK CUT TEMPLES</b></li><li>mandagapattu inscription refers to him as&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">VIVHITRACHITTA</b>, constructed temples of brahma, vishnu, shiva without using rocks, timber, metal and mortar</li><li>he wrote book:&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">MATTAVILASA PRAHASANA,&nbsp;</b>a satire play written in Sanskrit</li></ol><div><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase; font-size: 19.8px;">NARASIMHAVARMAN</b>&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase; font-size: 26.8px;">I</b>&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase; font-size: 19.8px;">630-668 AD</b><ol><li>a.k.a&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">MAMALLA</b>, means great&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">WRESTLER</b></li><li>he&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">FOUNDED MAMALLAPURAM</b></li><li>wanted to avenge death of his father at hands of&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">CHALUKYAS</b>&nbsp;ruler&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">PULAKESIN II</b></li><li>in battle of manimangalam near kanchi, he won</li><ol><li>mention of battle in&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">KURRAM</b>&nbsp;Copper Plates</li><li>pallav army completely destroyed Chalukyan army and captured city&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">VATAPI</b></li><li>Narasimhavarman I assumed title&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">VATAPIKONDA</b></li></ol><li>he also marched towards sri lanka, and restored throne to Manavarma</li><li>during his reign&nbsp;&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">HIUEN-TSANG CAME</b>, he gave vivid description of pallav city capital kanchipuram</li><ol><li>beautiful city, 6 miles circumference</li><li>100 monasteries, 10000 monks&nbsp;</li><li>great learning centre</li></ol><li><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">GREAT MONOLITHIC RATHAS</b>&nbsp;were erected during his reign</li></ol></div></div></div></div></div></div><div><br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"></div><div><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase; font-size: 21.8px;">NARASIMHAVARMAN&nbsp;II OR RAJASIMHA 695-722 AD</b><ol><li>his period is peaceful and more art and architecture development</li><li>built&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">SHORE TEMPLE</b>&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">AT MAMALLAPURAM AND KAILASANATHA TEMPLE KANCHIPURAM</b></li><li><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">DANDIN</b>, Sanskrit scholar in his court, wrote&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">DASHAKUMARACHARITA</b>&nbsp;</li><li>after that pallavas rule lasted till 9 Century</li><li><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">APARAJITA</b>:&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">LAST RULER&nbsp;</b>defeated by&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">CHOLA KING</b>&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">ADITYA I</b></li><li>end of pallava rulers</li></ol><div><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">ADMINISTRATION OF PALLAVAS</b><ol><li>symbol:&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">BULL&nbsp;</b>and lingam</li><li>well organized administration</li><li>state divided into&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">KOTTAMS</b>, head appointed by king</li><li>districts were divided into&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">NADU</b></li><li>king assisted by council</li><li>well trained army</li><li>land grants for temple:&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">DEVADHANA</b></li><li>land to brahmins:&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">BRAHMADEYA, TAX EXAMPTED</b></li><li>much focus on&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">IRRIGATION CANALS</b>&nbsp;and tanks&nbsp;</li><li>main tax source by traders, merchants, weavers etc</li><li>village assembly sabhas look after village&nbsp;</li><li>sabha of village worked with&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">URAR</b>, informal gathering of village population</li></ol><div><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">ARMY OF PALLAVAS</b><ol><li>foot-soldiers, cavalry and a small force of elephants</li><li>chariots were ineffective in hilly&nbsp;terrains</li><li>Navy and Dockyard at&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">MAMALLAPURAM</b></li><li>however pallava navy , was&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">MUCH SMALLER THAN CHOLAS NAVY</b></li></ol></div><div><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">TRADE</b><ol><li>barter system but later gold and silver coins came</li><li><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">MERCHANTS OBTAINED LICENSE TO TRADE</b></li><li><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">MAMALLAPURAM&nbsp;</b>important seaport</li><li>foreign trade, merchants called as&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">NANADESI</b>, south east asia&nbsp;</li><li>major income from maritime trade</li></ol></div><div><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">SOCIETY UNDER PALLAVAS</b><ol><li>Rigid&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">CASTE&nbsp;</b>system,&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">BRAHMINS&nbsp;</b>occupied high place, they also got land grants</li><li>Sat-Kshatriyas, class for wars</li><li>period saw&nbsp;rise of&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">SAIVISM&nbsp;</b>and&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">VAISHNAVISM</b></li><li><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">VEDIC&nbsp;</b>religion,&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">SHIVA&nbsp;</b>worship</li><li>buddha and jainism declined, bhakti movement also came</li><li>hymn in&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">TAMIL&nbsp;</b>language</li><li>temples of shiva and vishnu spread brahminism</li><li>influence of brahmanism</li><li><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">EVEN JAINISM WHICH EARLIER USED PRAKRIT AND SANSKRIT, USED TAMIL LANGUAGE TO STAY IN COMPETITION WITH BRAHMINISM</b></li><li>Mahendravarman I composed&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">MATTAVILASA PRAHASANA</b>, in sanskrit, which led to growth of sanskrit</li><li>Dandin wrote&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">DASHAKUMARACHARITA</b></li></ol><div><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">ROCK CUT TEMPLES</b><ol><li>Mahendravarman I introduced&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">ROCK&nbsp;</b>cut temples</li><li>Ellora caves and Ajanta caves date 500 to 950 AD</li><li>Ellora famous for&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">SCULPTURES</b></li><li>Ajanta famous for&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">PAINTINGS</b></li></ol><div><br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"></div></div><div><br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"></div><div><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">REVENUE AND TAXATION</b><ol><li>source of tax, rural, villages, lands</li><li>1/6th to 1/10th of produce</li></ol></div><div><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">IRRIGATION FACILITIES&nbsp;</b><ol><li>special land category,&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">ERIPATTI&nbsp;</b>or tank land only in south india</li><li>land donated by individuals and Revenue from this land is used to maintain village tanks</li><li>rain water harvesting facility</li></ol></div><div><br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"></div><div><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">EDUCATION AND LITERATURE</b><ol><li>great learning centre, capital&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">KANCHI</b></li><li><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">GHATIKA&nbsp;</b>popular at kanchi, attracted students</li><li>Mayurasharma, a Buddhist writer, founded&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">KADAMBA DYNASTY</b></li><li><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">DHARAMPALA</b>, who became head of Nalanda university, belonged to kanchi</li><li><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">DANDIN</b>,famous scholar also belonged to court of Narasimhavarman II</li><li><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">MAHENDRAVARMAN</b>&nbsp;I wrote Mattavilasa Prahasana, a satire play&nbsp;</li><li><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">TAMIL</b>&nbsp;literature developed in this period</li><li><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;"><i style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">DEVARAM&nbsp;</i></b>composed by Nayanmars</li><li><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;"><i style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">NALAYIRA&nbsp;DIVYA</i></b>&nbsp;Prabandham&nbsp;composed by Alwars represent the religious literature</li><li><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">PERUNDEVANAR</b>&nbsp;patronized by Nandivarman II, he translated <b>mahabharata </b>in <b>tamil </b>name as&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;"><i style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;">BHARAT VENBA</i></b></li><li>Another important book Nandikkalambagan</li></ol><div><br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"></div><div><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">PALLAVA ART AND ARCHITECTURE</b><ol><li>great age for temple building and&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">ROCK CUT TEMPLES</b></li><li>pallavas introduced art of excavating temple from rock cut</li><li>dravidian style temple began with pallavas</li><li>cave temples and&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">MONOLITHIC RATHAS</b></li><li>rock cut mainly introduced by Mahendravarman I</li><li>later monolithic rathas were found</li><li>five rathas Panchapandavar, signifies 5 style temples</li><li>later Rajasimha introduced&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">STRUCTURAL TEMPLES</b></li><li>built using soft sand rocks</li><li><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">KAILASANATHA</b>&nbsp;at kanchi and&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">SHORE TEMPLE</b>&nbsp;at mamallapuram fine example of structural temples</li><li>kailasanatha temple greatest architectural piece of pallava</li><li>open art gallery at Mamallapuram</li><li>Descent of Ganges or the penance of arjuna is called fresco painting in stone</li><li>figures of ascetic cat, elephants&nbsp;</li></ol><div><br style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif;"></div><div><b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">FINE ARTS OF PALLAVAS</b><ol><li>music, dance, painting developed</li><li>mamandur inscription contains note on notation of vocal music</li><li>dancing postures in sculptures</li><li>Sittannavasal painting</li><li>Mahendravarman I, with title of&nbsp;Chittirakkarapuli builder of temples, compile commentary on&nbsp;<b style="font-family: &quot;Nunito Sans&quot;, sans-serif; text-transform: uppercase;">DAKSHINACHITRA</b></li></ol></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div><b><br></b></div><div><br></div><div><div><b>CHALUKYAS&nbsp; 543-755 AD WILD BOAR</b></div><div><br></div><div><b>INTRO</b><ol><li>Founder:&nbsp;<b>PULAKESIN I</b>&nbsp;Chalukyas Dynasty near badami</li><li><i>Capital:</i><b style=""><i>&nbsp;</i>VATAPI</b>&nbsp;or Badami ( karnataka ) founded by&nbsp;<b>KIRTIVARMAN</b>&nbsp;.</li><li>two Chalukyas, Badami(Vatapi) and Kalyani</li><li>western Chalukyas ruled over area of deccan for 200 years</li><li>after Chalukyas, Rashtrakutas came in deccan</li></ol><div><br></div><div><img src="images/chalukya.JPG"></div><div><br></div><div><b>PULAKESIN II 608-642 AD</b><ol><li>most important ruler</li><li><b>Aihole inscription</b>&nbsp;issued by him composed by <b>Ravikrit</b>, a jain scholar (Karnataka) give details of reign</li><li>he fought against kadambas of banavasi and ganges of mysore</li><li>he <b>defeated Harshavardhana</b> on banks of river Narmada</li><li>but later&nbsp;<b>Narasimhavarman I, pallava ruler defeated Pulakesin I</b>&nbsp;near kanchi</li><li>his capital Vatapi captured and <b>destroyed</b> <b>by Narasimhavarman I</b>, Pulakesin II died</li><li>but later VIKRAMADITYA,successor of Pulakesin II plundered pallavas city</li><li>Hiuen-tsang also came during his period</li></ol><div><div><b>Kirtivarman II</b><ol><li>last ruler, defeated by&nbsp;<b>Dantidurga, founder of Rashtrakutas</b></li></ol><div><br></div></div></div></div></div></div><div><b>ADMINISTRATION OF CHALUKYAS</b><ol><li>Highly <b>Centralized</b></li><li>Royal Insignia:&nbsp;<b>Wild Boar</b></li><li>rule according to dharma-shastra and <b>Niti-shastra</b></li><li>but in pallavas and cholas, states were ruled by officers appointed by king</li><li>they had great maritime power, 100 ships in navy</li><li>importance to Vedic rites</li><li>performed&nbsp;<b><i>Ashvamedha</i></b>&nbsp;sacrifice, agnistoma, vajapeya</li><li><b>vishnu</b> and <b>shiva</b> temples emerged and buddhism decline, confirmed by Hiuen-tsang</li><li>but&nbsp;<b><i>Jainism rises</i></b>&nbsp;in this period</li><li><b>Ravikirti</b>, court poet of Pulakesin II, composed <b>Aihole</b> inscription, which contains harshavardhan defeat</li><li>Royal Women in Pallavas ladies as provincial governors</li></ol><div><b>King and Ministers</b><ol><li>PM: Pradhana</li><li>Foreign Ministers : maha <b>sandhi </b>vigraha</li><li>Revenue :<b>Amatya </b>Minister</li><li>Minister Exchequer: <b>Samaharta</b></li><li>Division of State: <b>Vishayam </b>&gt; Rastram &gt; <b>Nadu </b>&gt; Grama</li><li>Officials: Vishayapati, samantas, gramapohis, mahatras</li></ol><div><b>Provincial Administration</b></div><div><ol><li>king appointed his sons as provincial governors</li><li>title: Raja, marakka-rajan</li><li>Village:</li><ol><li>Nala-Kavundas as revenue officials</li><li>Kamunda head of village</li><li>Karana as village accountant</li><li>Mahapurush maintained law and order</li></ol></ol><div><b>Religion</b>&nbsp;<ol><li>Shaivism and vaishnavism</li><li>king performed yaganes</li><li>Title:&nbsp;parama-vaishana and parama-maheswara</li><li>worshipped <b>Karthikeyan</b>, the god of war</li><li>jainism also rises in this period, famous jain scholar Ravikirti</li><li>Hiuen-tsang also gave account of Buddhist centres</li></ol></div>Literature and Education of Chalukyas<ol><li>Chalukyas used <b>sanskrit </b>in pillar inscription Aihole and Mahakudam</li><li>Saptavataram, sanskrit book&nbsp;</li></ol></div></div><div><br></div><div>Art and architecture<ol><li>developed&nbsp;<b style="">Vesara</b>&nbsp;style in building structural temples</li><li>they introduced technique of building temple with soft <b>sandstones</b></li><li>temples were of shiva, vishnu and jain tirthankaras</li><li>mainly two types of temples</li><li>First: <b>structural </b>temples at Aihole, Badami, Pattadakal</li><li>Second: <b>cave </b>architecture, Ajanta, ellora and nasik, badami cave</li><li>Stages in temple</li><ol><li>first stage in Aihole and Badami</li><li>temples of Aihole</li><ol><li><b>ladh </b>khan temple</li><li><b>durga </b>temple resemble buddha chaitya</li><li><b>huchimalligudi </b>temple</li><li>jain temple at <b>meguti</b></li></ol><li>four rock cut temples at Badami</li><li>Second Stage by Pattadakal</li><li>4 in north and 6 in dravidian style</li><li>Virupaksha temple built by queen of Vikramaditya II</li></ol></ol><div>Architecture Places of Chalukyas Period<ol><li><b>Aihole </b>( Ayyavole )</li><ol><li>built in 634, HQ of famous medieval Ayyavole merchants' guild</li><li>70 temples in aihole</li><li>Ladkhan temple</li><li>Aihole Durga Temple, raised platform in semi-circle</li><li>Huccimalligudi durga temple in rectangular form</li><li>jain temples: Meguti Jain temple</li></ol><li>Vatapi Badami</li><ol><li>four&nbsp; caves in badami</li><li>largest cave temple built by Mangalesa of Vishnu god</li><li>vishnu resting on snake bed and Narasimha example of Chalukya Art</li></ol><li>Pattadakal</li><ol><li>village in <b>bagalkot</b> district of karnataka</li><li>Virupaksha temple built at order of Queen Lohamahadevi to commemorate conquest of Kanchipuram by her husband Vikramaditya II</li><li>structural temple of Rajasimha at Mamallapuram</li><li>here more than 10 temple of Chalukyas</li></ol></ol><div>Paintings of Chalukyas<ol><li>cave temples of badami contains paintings of Vishnu</li><li>painting style Vakataka, mainly focus on Vishnu</li></ol><div><br></div></div></div><div><br></div><div><b>RASHTRAKUTAS 755-975 AD</b><ol><li><b>kannada </b>origin, mother tongue Kannada</li><li><b>Dantidurga&nbsp;</b>founder of Rashtrakutas</li><li>he captured malwa region from gurjaras</li><li>later he annexed Chalukyas defeating Kirtivarman II</li></ol><div><br></div><div><b>Krishna I</b><ol><li>great ruler, defeated ganges and eastern Chalukyas of Vengi</li><li>he built famous <b>Kailasanatha</b> Temple of Ellora</li></ol><div><b>Amoghavarsha 815-880 AD</b><ol><li>ruled for 64 years, but lost control over malwa</li><li>followed jainism</li><li>wrote famous Kannada book, <b>Kavirajamarga</b></li><li>he made City of Malkhed as capital</li></ol><div><b>Krishna III 936-968</b><ol><li>fought with cholas and defeated them at Thakkolam</li><li>captured Tanjore</li><li>built Krishneswara temple at Rameswaram</li><li>he controlled region of Tondaimandalam including capital Kanchi</li><li>after his death Rashtrakutas declined</li></ol><div><br></div><div><b>Administration</b><ol><li>Empire &gt; Rashtras &gt; Vishayasyas &gt; <b>Bhuktis&nbsp;</b></li><li>Rashtras:Rashtrapati</li><li>Vishayasyas or districts :Vishayapati</li><li><b>Bhuktis</b>, consists of 50 to 70 villages: Bhogapathi, appointed by govt.</li><li>villages under village headmen</li></ol><div><b>Society and Economy</b><ol><li>vaishnavism and Shaivism, flourished</li><li>but jainism rises, patronized by kings</li><li>over 1/3rd population of Deccan followed Jainism</li><li>Salatogi, college in Bijapur district</li><li>trade with arabs</li></ol><div><b>Cultural&nbsp;</b><ol><li>patronized Sanskrit&nbsp;</li><li>Trivikrama wrote: Nala Champu</li><li>Halayudha wrote: Kavi Rahasya during Krishan III</li><li>jain literature flourished</li><li>Jinasena composed Parsva Budaya, a biography of parsva in verses</li><li>Gunabhadra wrote: Adipurana, life stories of jains</li><li>Sakatayana wrote: Amoga Vritti</li><li>Viracharya wrote: Ganitasaram</li><li>kannada literature rise</li><li><b>Amoghavarsha</b>, wrote <b>Kavirajamarga </b>first poetic work in <b>Kannada </b>language</li><li>Pampa great kannada poet, wrote <b>Vikramasenavijaya</b></li><li>Ponna another famous kannada poet wrote Santipurana</li></ol><div><br></div><div><b>Art and Architecture</b>&nbsp;<ol><li>most famous Ellora and Elephanta</li><li><b>ellora</b>,&nbsp;<b>Kailasanatha temple of Rashtrakutas</b>, during Krishna I</li><li>carved out from 200 feet long and 100 in breadth and height</li><li>temple has four parts</li><ol><li>main shrine</li><li>entrance</li><li>intermediate</li><li>mandapa surrounding courtyard</li><li>figures of elephants and lions</li><li>3 tier sikhara</li><li>inside 16 square pillars</li><li>goddess durga slaying buffalo demon</li><li>ravana making attempt to lift mount kailash</li></ol><li>elephanta caves near bombay</li><li>at entrance dwarapalakas</li><li>in walls forms of shiva, natarajan, gangadhara, ardhanareeswara, somaskanda</li><li>figure of <b>trimurti</b></li></ol></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div>
    </div>`}


    ,{ title: "Bahamni and Vijay Nagar  ",content:`<input id="chapter" placeholder="Chapter" value="Bahamni and Vijay Nagar">
        <input class="subtitle" placeholder="Chapter Name" value="">
        <div class="editor" contenteditable="true"><div><br></div><div>Introduction</div><div>Delhi Sultanate in north</div><div>South kingdoms Four</div><div><ol><li>Yadavas of Devagiri present Maharashtra</li><li>Hoysalas of Dvarasmudra Karnataka</li><li>Kakatiyas of Warangal Present Telangana</li><li>Pandyas of Madhurai Southern Tamil Nadu</li></ol><div>1304 and 1310 <b>Malik Kafur</b> attacked and raid using sultanate army</div><div>Tughluq also continued attacks</div><div><b>MBT</b> 1325-51&nbsp;</div><div>even tried to make <b>Devagiri</b> rename as <b>Daulatabad</b> as capital</div><div>but failed and went back to delhi</div><div>Those left declared independence</div><div><br></div><div><b>Zafar Khan </b>declared <b>independence</b> at Devagiri 1345</div><div>shifted capital to <b>Gulbarga in northern Karnataka</b></div>Took Title: Bahman Shah and founded Bahmani Dynasty 1347-1527</div><div>almost 180 years</div><div><br></div><div>1336 Vijaynagar established by Sangam bros Harihara and Bukka at Vijaynagara(Hampi)</div><div><br></div><div>Rivals: over rich <b>Raichur Doab</b>, sea ports of Goa, <b>important supply points for horses</b> needed for army</div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div>Source of above text</div><div><br></div><div><ol><li>Manucharitra</li><ol><li>written by grandfather of Telugu poetry Allasani Peddana</li><li>one of 8 poets in court of krishna dev ray, the Astadiggajalu</li><li>Telugu language, contains short story from Markandeya Puranam</li></ol><li>Saluvabhyudayam</li><ol><li>Rajanatha Dindima II wrote</li><li>poems on wars of Saluva Narasimha</li><li>he also wrote Achyutabhyudaya (also called as Achyutarayabhyudaya) on king Achyuta Raya.</li></ol><li>Rayavachakamu</li><ol><li>by&nbsp;Pemmasani Ramalinga Nayudu, a commander in krishna dev ray army</li><li>mention of Nayankara system in Krishna dev ray</li><li>Nayakara System</li><ol><li>a feudal lord relation between rulers and nayaks</li><li>generals were given lands, in return nayaks paid revenue to rulers</li><li>nayakas gave lands to tenants and extracted as much as 10% of total produce</li><li>nayakas maintained standing army which was used by rulers</li></ol></ol></ol><div><br></div></div><div>Travelers</div><div><span style="font-size: 16.8px;">Ibn Battuta
a Moroccan traveller (1333-45)</span></div><div><span style="font-size: 16.8px;">wrote <b>Rihala</b></span></div><div><span style="font-size: 16.8px;"><br></span></div><div><span style="font-size: 16.8px;">Abdur
Razzak from Persia (1443–45)</span></div><div><span style="font-size: 16.8px;"><br></span></div><div><span style="font-size: 16.8px;">Nikitin, a
Russian (1470–74)</span></div><div><span style="font-size: 16.8px;"><br></span></div><div><span style="font-size: 16.8px;">the Portuguese visitors&nbsp;Domingo Paes and Nuniz (1520–37)
provide remarkably rich information</span></div><div><br></div><div>Coins: Vijaynagar gold coins called Varaha</div><div>image of hindu deities, bull, elephant</div><div>gandaberunda : eagle holding elephant</div><div>king's name in <b>NAGARI</b> SCRIPT OR KANNADA SCRIPT</div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div></div>`}




]